<HEADLINE> Southern African Businesses Urged to Raise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Southern Africa has a major
problem of competitiveness and businessmen have to change their
way of management, said a leader of the Institute of Directors
(IoD) in Southern Africa Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Manning, chairman of the IoD, made the statement at
the opening of the Joint Convention between the IoD Zimbabwe and
IoD in Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the two-day convention is: "At the crossroads? --
Doing business in Southern Africa".
</P>
<P>
Manning said: "We have a major competitiveness problem in the
region and the question is how quickly to change the way we manage
our organizations".
</P>
<P>
It is dangerous for business people to assume that they have
found the formula for success because things are constantly
changing, he said. He noted that the world of the year 2000
will be quite different from that of 1995 and is going to change
at an accelerated pace with the life cycles of industries being
shortened.
</P>
<P>
Every business, he said, faces the danger of probable decline
and companies are in a race to make a difference to their
customers in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
He urged managers to adapt themselves to the Changing world so
as to solve the problem of competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
