<HEADLINE> EU Still Concerned Over U.S. Trade Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
in its newly published report that the European Union (EU) is
still concerned seriously over trade barriers preventing European
businesses from operating in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive released the annual report on U.S. barriers to
trade and investment, saying the extra-territoriality "is a
long-standing and growing feature of the U.S. legal system
manifesting itself in - among others - the fields of environment,
banking, tax and export control".
</P>
<P>
"While the EU may share some of the objections underlying such
laws, it is opposed, as a matter of law and principle, to the
extraterritorial application of domestic legislation insofar as it
purports to force persons present in - and companies incorporated
in - the EU to follow U.S. laws or policies outside the U.S. and
to the extent that it serves only to protect U.S. trade or
political interests," the report said.
</P>
<P>
For the moment, at least, the two most insidious U.S. laws as
far as the EU is seriously concerned over appear to have been
suspended, the Commission said, referring to the Helms Burton
Libertad Act of 1996 targeting foreign trade with Cuba and the
1996 Iran and Libya Sanctions Act (ILSA).
</P>
<P>
However, "variations of the same problem can be found in, inter
alia, various environmentally-driven embargoes, export control
legislation, as well as, at the sub-federal level, selective
purchasing laws," the report points out.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive noted "an unwelcome development" with the
introduction of several sub-federal selective purchasing laws in
public procurement, citing an example that the Massachusetts Burma
law is restricting the ability of EU and other companies doing
business with specific countries to bid for contracts in various
states and cities. The law acted because of human rights concerns
in Burma, the report added.
</P>
<P>
These concern investment restrictions, lengthy proceedings,
conditionality of market access and reciprocity-based procedures.
"This situation is not in line with the open market access policy
advocated by the U.S.," the European Union executive added.
</P>
</TEXT>
