<HEADLINE> Greek PM Pledges to Help Earthquake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis pledged here Thursday that his government would do its
duty to repair the damage caused by Tuesday's devastating
earthquake and restore normality to the tens of thousands of
families in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after accepting cheques donated by shipowners, Simitis
said that the catastrophic results of the earthquake would be
dealt with by all of Greeks together.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that 200 million drachmas (about 666,666.7 U.S.
dollars) would be handed over to the Health and Welfare Ministry
which had already launched a fund-raising drive.
</P>
<P>
So far, the death toll of the earthquake registering 5.9 on the
Richter scale has climbed to 83 as efforts by rescue teams
continue to release those still trapped under the rubble in the
worst-hit areas of northwestern Athens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
