<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts Continue to Resolve Coalition Crisis in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Officials from Israel's
Finance Ministry and Education Ministry continued their efforts
Thursday to find a way out of a coalition crisis over the
governmental funding of religious schools.
</P>
<P>
The powerful ultra-Orthodox religious party Shas has threatened
to quit the coalition of Prime Minister Ehud Barak if the
government does not transfer 12 million shekels (about 2.85
million U.S. dollars) to its educational networks before the
beginning of the Jewish New Year, which falls on Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of teachers in the party's schools have not received
their salaries for the last three month.
</P>
<P>
Finance and education officials have insisted that Shas has to
formulate a reform plan before the transfer of money can be made,
citing reports that millions of shekels have been wasted due to
mismanagement and alleged corruption.
</P>
<P>
The religious institutes enjoyed preferential treatment in the
three years of rule of the former right-wing prime minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, raising resentment among the secular public.
</P>
<P>
In the campaign leading to his election victory in May, Barak
pledged to change the national priorities and stop the overflow of
money to the religious schools and institutes.
</P>
<P>
But Barak has apparently backed down from his domestic reform
plan since he included the Shas, the third largest party in the
parliament, in his coalition in order to garner wide support for
his goal to move forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
If the 17 Shas legislators walked away, Barak's coalition
would be reduced to a 51-seat minority as another ultra-religious
party, the United Torah Judaism, which controls five seats,
announced a few days ago to quit the cabinet to protest Barak's
consent to transporting heavy power equipment on Shabath, the
Jewish weekend when driving is banned by religious laws.
</P>
<P>
To protest over the funding crisis, Shas boycotted a
parliamentary voting Wednesday night on the latest peace accord
Barak signed with Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser
Arafat Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Due to the Shas boycott, the agreement was approved only by a
narrow majority of 52-23 and with the help of 10 Arab legislators,
who sit outside the government.
</P>
<P>
But the possibility of Shas quitting the coalition is
relatively low since the party, which represents low-income Middle
East Jews, has to depend on the government to fund its generous
educational and welfare networks, which have contributed to its
election success.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Wednesday that the salaries of the teachers in
Shas' schools should be paid before a comprehensive review of the
educational system of the party can be made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
