<HEADLINE> 11 Iraqi Civilians Injured in Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Eleven Iraqi civilians were
injured on Thursday in U.S.-British warplanes' attacks on
civilian targets in southern Iraq, an Iraqi military spokesman
announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 9:15 (0515 GMT) and 12:05 (0805
GMT), a total of 36 formations of U.S. and British warplanes
coming from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases violated southern Iraqi
airspace over Basrah, Thi-Qar, Muthana, Najaf and Qadisiyah
provinces.
</P>
<P>
These enemy warplanes bombed some civilian and service
facilities in the region and injured 11 civilians, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back at the enemy planes
and forced them to flee to their bases, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ten formations of U.S. and British warplanes coming from
Turkish airspace violated northern Iraqi airspace over Neineva,
Erbil and Dohuk provinces at 10:00 (0600 GMT) in the day,
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have made 12,283 sorties over the two no-fly
zones in Iraq, and have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian
facilities and military sites, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led
western allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed
aim of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite
Muslims in the south from attacks by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
