<HEADLINE> Israel to Deliver Redeployment Map to Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 9 (Xinhua)-- Israel has decided to
deliver Thursday evening a map of troop redeployments in the
West Bank to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and explain to him
from which area Israel will pull out its troops, Israel Radio
said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian officials met behind the closed doors
Thursday and discussed in details about the troop redeployment map
prepared by Israel in order to carry out the newly signed Sharm
El-Sheikh agreement, the Radio quoted government and military
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
So far, no details about the redeployment map have been
disclosed, but Tourism Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak told the
Radio Thursday that the new map prepared by the Israeli military
is similar to the old one prepared by the previous government.
</P>
<P>
No significant changes were made to the old map, but the
Israeli military will hand over more territories of northern
West Bank to the Palestinians in the future redeployment, Shahak
added.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm El-Sheikh agreement, the Israeli military is
first to redeploy from 7 percent of the West Bank, transferring
it from Israeli-controlled Area C to Palestinian
civilians-controlled Area B.
</P>
<P>
On November 15, a 2 percent transfer will be made from Area C
to full Palestinian controlled Area A and 3 percent from Area C
to Area B. In January next year, a 1 percent transfer will take
place from Area C to Area and 5.1 percent from Area C to Area A.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Israeli cabinet approved the redeployment
map and the first 7 percent troop redeployment while the
Knesset (parliament) ratified the Sharm El-Sheikh peace accord,
paving the way for future troop redeployment from the West
Bank and Thursday's release of 200 Palestinian prisoners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
