<HEADLINE> Egyptian Police Officials to Be Interrogated for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Interior Minister Habib
el-Adli referred three top police officials in Port Said to a
disciplinary council on Thursday for interrogation for failure to
perform their duty during a visit there by President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Monday, Mubarak was attacked and slightly injured by a
knife-wielding man described as an Islamic fanatic when the
president was riding to a meeting in the Mediterranean port, 180
kilometers northeast of Cairo, at the northern end of the Suez
Canal.
</P>
<P>
The three officers are Port Said Security Director Maj. Gen.
Hassan Abdel Motteleb Othman Jebril, Director of State Security
Investigation Maj. Gen. Abdullah Nasr and Criminal Investigation
Director Brig. Mohammad Sallem Shalan, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
If convicted by the disciplinary council, they will face
dismissal and revocation of pension and benefits, an Interior
Ministry official said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The three officials were transferred to other posts outside the
Port Said Directorate as of Tuesday, the news agency said without
mentioning their new posts.
</P>
<P>
El-Adli on Wednesday appointed Maj. Gen. Mohammad Farid
Hassanein, Maj. Gen. Nazih Gad and former Deputy Security Director
of Giza Governorate Brig. Azmi Badawi to replace the three
officials in question, it said.
</P>
<P>
Also Thursday, the interior minister dismissed Mohamed Hani
al-Ezaby as the intelligence chief and gave him the post of the
border security chief, the news agency said. Al-Ezaby was replaced
by his deputy, Salah Eddin Mustafa Salama, it added.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Arabic-language daily Al-Ahram
published on Thursday, Mubarak blamed the attack on lax security.
He singled out the three Port Said security heads, and said he
will order security reviews in all areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
