<HEADLINE> S. Africa Enacts Law to Seize Criminals' Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Tuesday put
into force a law that would allow the seizure of criminals' assets
 retrospectively.
</P>
<P>
The controversial Prevention of Organized Crime Second
Amendment Act was signed by Acting President Jacob Zuma on Monday,
according to a Government Gazette published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In three recent high-profile cases, High Court judges
overturned seizures under the principal act on the grounds that
the assets involved were acquired before the legislation came into
force on January 21.
</P>
<P>
The amendment seeks to make the act retrospective.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party and the Freedom Front were the only
parties to oppose the legislation when it was approved by
parliament last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
