<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Mining Output Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's total
mining output for the three months to July 1999 decreased by 1.1
percent after seasonal adjustment compared with the previous three
months, Statistics South Africa said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The slip was mainly due to a reduction in gold output, besides
the exceptional decline in June's output, which was 4.3 percent
lower than May, the state statistical bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The yield of non-gold minerals reflected a slight increase of
0.3 percent after seasonal adjustment during this period, mainly
due to increases in the production of copper, platinum and
manganese.
</P>
<P>
The value of mineral sales maintains a declining trend, the
bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Both gold (-7.0 percent) and non-gold (-3.5 percent) sales
contributed to the decrease of 4.8 percent in the total seasonally
adjusted mineral sales during the three months to June 1999
compared with the previous three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
