<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF May Help Romania Avoid Financial Crisis: Moody's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Inferior ratings granted for
the loan risk of Romania reflects economic confusion and political
dissension which place the country in front of a major financial
crisis, commented the local Nine O'clock daily on Thursday citing
a recent report on Romania made by the international rating agency
Moody's.
</P>
<P>
The rating for Romania - B3 for the debt in foreign currency,
Caa1 for banking deposits in foreign currency and Caa1 for the
debt in home currency, are accompanied by a perspective of steady
rating, because they already express "a very big probability of an
incapacity of payment," Moody's said.
</P>
<P>
If the new accord with International Monetary Fund (IMF) signed
in August is implemented successfully, Romania could avoid the
financial crisis. However, Moody's recalled that "four previous
programs with IMF ended prematurely because Romania failed to meet
its obligations."
</P>
<P>
"Compliance with the program assumed with IMF will also open
the way for other financing from other external official sources,
such as the World Bank. Under such conditions, the foreign
currency resources of Romania will become enough to cover the
payment obligations of external debt on the short term," Moody's
explained.
</P>
<P>
Romania has an external debt estimated at 9.6 billion U.S.
dollars representing roughly 26 percent of its GDP, the Moody's
report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
