<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Humanitarian Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday said that "understanding causes is the first
step to successful prevention" of the humanitarian challenges.
namely the natural disasters and armed conflicts in the world at
large.
</P>
<P>
The statement was contained in Annan's annual report on the
work of the United Nations, which, released here Thursday, is to
be submitted to the upcoming 54th General Assembly session,
scheduled for September 14.
</P>
<P>
On natural disasters, Annan said, "The world has experienced
three times as many great natural disasters in the 1990s as in the
1960s -- while emergency aid funds have declined by 40 percent in
the past five years alone, according to the International
Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies.
</P>
<P>
"Today's disasters are sometimes man-made, and human action
--or inaction-- exacerbates virtually all of them," he said,
"Poverty and population pressures increase the costs of natural
hazards because more and more people have been forced to live in
harms' way -- on flood plains, earthquake-prone zones and unstable
hillsides."
</P>
<P>
"Unsustainable development practices also contribute to the
rising impact of natural hazards," he said.
flooding."
</P>
<P>
On Conflicts, he said, "the most worrying development in 1998
was a significant increase in the number of wars."
</P>
<P>
"In recent years, poor countries have been far more likely to
be embroiled in armed conflicts than rich ones," he said.
"Economic decline is also strongly associated with violent
conflict, not least because the politics of a shrinking economy
are inherently more conflictual than those of economic growth."
</P>
<P>
"But in other cases, armed conflict has less to do with ethnic,
national or other enmities than the struggle to control economic
resources," he said. "The pursuit of diamonds, drugs, timber
concessions and other valuable commodities drives a number of
today's internal wars," which are the main characteristics of
today's armed conflicts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
