<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unfair Media Attention Contributes to Humanitarian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday blamed the unfair media attention for part
of the causes for a lack of consistent response by the
international community to humanitarian emergencies, such as the
conflicts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the statement in his annual report on the work of
the Organization, which is issued here Thursday. The report will
be considered by the upcoming 54th session of the General
Assembly, which is to open on September 14.
</P>
<P>
"The humanitarian challenge is heightened by the fact that the
international community does not respond in a consistent way to
humanitarian emergencies," he said. "Media attention is part of
the problem."
</P>
<P>
"The crisis in Kosovo, for example, received saturation
coverage," he said. "The more protracted and deadly war between
Eritrea and Ethiopia, and the resumption of Angola's savage
civil war received very little."
</P>
<P>
"Other wars went almost entirely unreported," he said. "Partly
for that reason, responses to appeals for humanitarian and
security assistance have been similarly skewed."
</P>
<P>
"It is my strong view that such assistance should not be
allocated on the basis of media coverage, politics or geography,"
he said. "Its sole criterion should be human need."
</P>
<P>
"I am particularly alarmed by the international community's
poor response to the needs of victims of war and natural
disasters in Africa," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Lessons from Kosovo crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Thursday three lessons can be learned from the
diplomatic failure in preventing recent crises, including the
crisis in Kosovo, a Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remarks in his annual work report to the
upcoming 54th session of the General Assembly, which is to open on
September 14. The report was issued here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On the lessons drawn from the recent failure in conflict
prevention, Annan said, "First, that if the primacy of the
Security Council with respect to the maintenance of international
peace and security is rejected, the very foundations of
international law as represented by the Charter will be brought
into question."
</P>
<P>
"No other universally accepted legal basis for constraining
wanton acts of violence exists," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Second, the conflict prevention, peacekeeping and peacemaking
must not become an area of competition between the United Nations
and regional organizations," he said. "Work together best when we
respect each other's prerogatives and sensitivities."
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Charter, the Security Council has the primary
responsibility for the maintenance of the world peace and
international security. However, the U.S.-led NATO, a military and
regional bloc, launched 79-day air strikes on Yugoslavia, a
sovereign country, without the authorization of the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
"Third, that prevention can only succeed with strong
political commitment from Member States and if the provision of
resources is adequate," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Lessons from Kosovo crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday three lessons can be learned from the
diplomatic failure in preventing recent crises, including the
crisis in Kosovo, a Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remarks in his annual work report to the
upcoming 54th session of the General Assembly, which is to open on
September 14. The report was issued here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On the lessons drawn from the recent failure in conflict
prevention, Annan said, "First, that if the primacy of the
Security Council with respect to the maintenance of international
peace and security is rejected, the very foundations of
international law as represented by the Charter will be brought
into question."
</P>
<P>
"No other universally accepted legal basis for constraining
wanton acts of violence exists," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Second, the conflict prevention, peacekeeping and peacemaking
must not become an area of competition between the United Nations
and regional organizations," he said. "Work together best when we
respect each other's prerogatives and sensitivities."
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Charter, the Security Council has the primary
responsibility for the maintenance of the world peace and
international security. However, the U.S.-led NATO, a military and
regional bloc, launched 79-day air strikes on Yugoslavia, a
sovereign country, without the authorisation of the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
"Third, that prevention can only succeed with strong
political commitment from Member States and if the provision of
resources is adequate," he said.
</P>
<P>
"During the 1990s, we have witnessed major challenges in the
patterns of global conflict and in the international community's
responses to them."
</P>
<P>
"Today, more than 90 percent of armed conflicts take place
within, rather than between, States," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Sanctions have been used far more frequently in the 1990s
than ever before, but with results that are ambiguous at best,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-09 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Palestinians Exhilarated Over Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAMALLAH, WEST BANK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- When a bus full of
Palestinian political prisoners pulled in at the compound of the
Palestinian Presidential Office, cheers broke out among scores of
their relatives and friends, and a teenager girl was seen climbing
into the window to meet her father before the bus fully stopped.
</P>
<P>
The 52 Palestinians in the bus were among the 199 Palestinian
political prisoners released by Israel Thursday as part of the
implementation of a new Israeli-Palestinian peace deal signed in
the Egyptian Red Sea Resort of Sharm El-Sheikh last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The other released prisoners returned to the Gaza Strip and
another West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Beaming with smiles or wiping joyful tears, the prisoners,
their parents, their children and friends exchange hugs and
cried out grateful prayers.
</P>
<P>
A military band struck up a tune and an old man danced to the
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
"I feel good and happy," said Ahmamoud Nasir, 36, one of the
prisoners. Propped by his friends, he looked pale and infirm after
spending over 14 years in Israeli jails on conviction of wounding
two Israelis in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"We are not against peace, but we need peace which will
guarantee the rights of the Palestinian people," he said,
referring to the current peacemaking between the Palestinians and
the new government of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The release of Palestinian political prisoners was the first
concrete step the Israeli side took to implement the revised Wye
accord Prime Minister Ehud Barak signed with Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for the release of 350 Palestinian
political prisoners, those jailed for anti-Israeli activity before
the signing of the Oslo accords in September 1993. The second
batch will be released in October.
</P>
<P>
In the coming days, Israel will also carry out the first stage
of three troop withdrawals, transferring 7 percent of the West Bank
to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also launch the permanent peace talks,
which deal with thorny issues like Palestinian statehood and
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"It is a nice step toward the right direction," Deputy PNA
Planning Minister Anees Barghoti told Xinhua before the bus
arrived. "We hope to see more steps by Israel," he said.
</P>
<P>
Barghoti expressed "cautious optimism" over the prospect of
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that Mr. Barak is serious about the process. He
showed courage in the Knesset yesterday when he said the
Palestinians should be given equal rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the remarks Barak made in a Knesset
(Israeli parliament) debate Wednesday night before the latest
agreement was approved by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
"We as a responsible government...we must take difficult,
sometimes painful decisions to peacefully separate from the
Palestinians, not to continue to rule over them," Barak said.
</P>
<P>
The release of Palestinian prisoners is an emotional issue for
the Palestinians as almost every family had a member or relative
jailed by Israel at a certain point in the last three decades
since Israel seized Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
It had also been one of the thorny issues in
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Weeks of bloody conflicts erupted late last year when former
hard-line Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu included 150
criminals, instead of political prisoners as expected by the
Palestinians, in the first group of 250 prisoners released.
</P>
<P>
In the latest negotiations, the two sides had been also at odds
over the number and terms of the prisoners to be released.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians had initially demanded that Israel release
650 political prisoners, but Israel insisted that it would
release not more than 500 and would have the rights to include
common criminals.
</P>
<P>
They finally concurred on the release of 350 political
prisoners with an Israeli promise to release more in the future.
</P>
<P>
Among the 199 prisoners released Thursday, 150 were jailed for
killing Palestinians who had cooperated with Israeli security
services, and 15 were involved in the wounding of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Israel has insisted that it would not release those who
murdered Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Tears welled up in the eyes of Salam Abudullah Bargouti, 75,
after all the prisoners got off the bus but his son, Nayel, did
not show up. Nayel, 44, has spent 23 years in jail after being
convicted of killing an Israeli Jew.
</P>
<P>
"We call for the release of more prisoners and more important
prisoners," said Palestinian Legislative Council member Marwan
Barghoti, who is also head of the Fatah Movement in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said those who had killed Israelis before the signing of the
Oslo accords should also be released. "There were wars between the
two sides at that time. Everyone was proud of what they did in the
wars. Of course, the situation has been different after 1993," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the upcoming transfer of land, Barghoti said the
size of the land is small, so nothing significant will
change. "But it will give the people some hope," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Satisfied With Measles Elimination in Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) said on Thursday it is satisfied with the elimination of
measles strategies it recommended for southern Africa which are
now as effective as those being applied in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The strategies include high routine vaccination coverage where
every child under one year is vaccinated to prevent them from
contracting such diseases as measles and polio.
</P>
<P>
WHO southern African expanded program on immunization advisor
Robin Biellik said since the countries in the region initiated
these strategies, the results had been very encouraging.
</P>
<P>
"From what we can tell, measles have actually been stopped in
Zimbabwe and Botswana," he told the delegates who are attending a
WHO workshop in Harare.
</P>
<P>
He said in Namibia and South Africa it was confirmed there were
still a few cases of measles transmission with 20 and 40 cases
reported this year.
</P>
<P>
"When we compare that with thousands of cases they had before,
this is a massive improvement which shows that the measles
elimination strategies recommended by WHO for use all over the
world appear to be working very well in southern Africa," he said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Military to Phase Out Support Squadron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian military will
phase out a support squadron based at Greenwood in the western
province of Nova Scotia, Local media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 434 Squadron is deemed non-combat related and will be
phased out over two years. The work at the Greenwood base will
then be privatized, the report quoted military sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The squadron is composed of Challenger aircraft and T-33 jets,
which provide support for electronic warfare training, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
The move, which will eliminate 225 military jobs, is part of
cuts to be taken by the Canadian air force, which plans to remove
more than 50 support aircraft from the flight lines.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien was quoted Thursday as
ruling out the grounding of the country's Snowbirds aerobatics
team consisting of 14 ageing Tutor aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the military put it impractical to keep
Tutors just for the sake of Snowbirds, which perform at Canada Day
celebrations every year.
</P>
<P>
The military wants to concentrate its work on the upgrading of
its frontline CF-18 fighter fleet and Aurora patrol planes,
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
