<HEADLINE> International Police Cooperation Should Strengthen States: France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- French Interior Minister Jean-
Pierre Chevenement said on Thursday that international cooperation
between police forces of different nations should be aimed at
strengthening individual states.
</P>
<P>
He said that Western countries have a "group responsibility" in
fighting international organized criminal groups.
</P>
<P>
"The bilateral cooperation should be carried out with the same
democratic norms, which are those of rule of law, and respect for
individual freedom and public freedom," said Chevenement in a
speech addressed to the French attaches in charge of security
issues posted in embassies and consulates around the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that the world security situation is experiencing an
unprecedented development and French security officials should
regard safeguarding the interior security of France as their
priorities.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the integration of central and eastern
European countries into the European Union is providing a good
chance to experiment with international police cooperation in
fighting organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
About 100 French security attaches posted in 56 countries are
meeting here this week to discuss "the challenges of the 21st
century" in the field of security.
</P>
<P>
These security officials, who belong to the organization of
Service of International Technical Cooperation of Police, carried
out 823 cooperative actions with their foreign counterparts in
1998, mostly in Africa, Europe, America and the Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
