<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Legislative Hearing Held in Guangzhou (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The People's Congress of
Guangdong Province in south China today hosted the country's first
legislative hearings as they listened to the opinions of twenty
local people from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
"As a Chinese citizen, I'm honored to attend this hearing,"
said Duan Lixing, a local official with the provincial water
conservancy bureau.
</P>
<P>
The hearing is designed to hear opinions on the recension of a
draft for an administrative regulation on construction-project
bidding.
</P>
<P>
Before the hearing, Duan spent a week studying the draft and
worked out detailed suggestions for amendments. "It's delightful
to have an opportunity to provide legislative advice for the
congress," he said.
</P>
<P>
Presided over by members of the construction environment and
resources protection committee of the congress, the hearing is
open freely to citizens, but the number of people participating is
limited to 20.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Senlin, director of the standing committee of the congress,
said that as China's first legislative hearing, it will play a
significant role in promoting the country's legislative
democratization.
</P>
<P>
"Through hearing, we can collect opinions from related
departments as well as individuals," Zhu said, and they will
provide valuable analyses and argumentation on regulations and
laws.
</P>
<P>
The hearing is also a way of making the legislation concrete,
practical and transparent, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Li Boqiao, a law professor at Jinan University, noted that the
hearing is a landmark in China's local legislative democratization.
</P>
<P>
The legislative hearing is based on the Constitution of People'
s Republic of China, which prescribes that all power in China
belongs to the people. The organs through which the people
exercise state power are the National People's Congress and the
local people's congresses at different levels, Li said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
