<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official on Preparation for Smooth Transfer of Power of Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China and Portugal are working
hard to create a favorable environment and making necessary
preparations for the smooth transfer of power of Macao, a Chinese
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Meeting a group of journalists from China's state media
organizations, Han Zhaokang, leader of the Chinese members of the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group, said since its establishment
in January 1988, the liaison group has held 36 plenary meetings
and innumerable meetings of specialized working groups and experts.
During these meetings, in-depth consultations were held between
the Chinese and Portuguese sides, within the framework of the Sino-
Portuguese Joint Declaration on the Question of Macao, on various
issues concerning the stable transition and smooth transfer of
power of Macao.
</P>
<P>
Han listed, in particular, three questions which the Chinese
side is most concerned about, namely, the localization of public
servants, the localization of laws and the official status of the
Chinese languages in Macao. He said big headway has been made in
these issues. A large number of Chinese public servants have taken
leading positions in Macao, and Sino-Portuguese consultations on
the civil procedural law, the last of the five leading laws, have
been close to completion. The four others, the criminal law, the
criminal procedural law, the civil law and the commercial law,
have realized the localization.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, the status and the use of the Chinese
language in the administrative, legislative and judicial areas
have been strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Han said that under the Sino-Portuguese joint declaration, the
future Macao Special Administrative Region can maintain and
develop ties with various countries, regions, and international
and regional organizations in certain fields under the name "China
Macao." To implement this regulation, he said, the liaison group
has reached consensus on Macao's continued participation in 46
international or regional organizations and continued application
of 124 international conventions to Macao after 1999.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the long-term interests of the Sino-
Portuguese relations, the Chinese side has also taken a flexible
and practical attitude toward certain questions, including the
nationalities of Macao residents and the schools of the Portuguese
language.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the two sides of the liaison group have intensified
discussion on the ceremony for transfer of power of Macao, Han
said. China will resume the exercise of sovereignty over Macao on
December 20 this year.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of stationing troops in Macao, Han said the
Chinese side hopes the Portuguese side will take into
consideration the long-term friendship and cooperation between the
two countries and strengthen cooperation on the Macao issue.
</P>
<P>
Han said he is confident of the smooth transfer of power of
Macao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Jobless Claims Fall Unexpectedly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department said
Thursday that the number of new claims for unemployment benefits
dropped unexpectedly last week.
</P>
<P>
The Department reported that 286,000 people filed new claims
for jobless benefits for the week ending September 4, down by 4,000
from the previous week. That was the lowest level since August 21,
when claims were at 285,000.
</P>
<P>
However, the four-week moving average for claims was up
slightly to 287,500 last week. That was the highest level since
August 8, when claims were at 288,250.
</P>
<P>
Some economists said last week's decrease in new claims was not
expected. they had been forecasting that new claims would actually
rise a little to 290,000. They said that's good news for workers
but is potentially worrisome. They worry that employers scrambling
for workers may woo them with higher wages and benefits, costs
that may drive up prices.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government said the nation's unemployment rate
ticked down to 4.2 percent in August, returning to a 29-year low.
In July, the rate was 4.3 percent. The unemployment report also
said that businesses added only 124,000 jobs to their payrolls and
that hourly earnings rose slightly.
</P>
<P>
Even though that report buoyed financial markets, investors,
more recently, have worried about the prospects of the Federal
Reserve raising interest rates again this year.
</P>
<P>
The Department's report said that for the week ending August 28,
33 states and territories reported decreases in new jobless claim
applications, while 20 reported increases. The state data lag a
week behind the national figures.
</P>
<P>
The state with the biggest decrease was California, down 1,990
while the state with the biggest increase was New York, up 1,216.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
