<HEADLINE> Greece, Turkey to Promote Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Turkey began their
second round of talks here Thursday in order to create a healthy
climate for the improvement of their strained bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day talks, senior Foreign Ministry officials
from both sides will discuss possibilities for cooperation in
economy, trade, tourism, environment and prevention of natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) quoted diplomatic
sources as saying that a draft accord based on the results of the
first round of talks could be considered if officials continued to
work on what they had achieved before.
</P>
<P>
The next round of talks between the two countries is to be
held in the Turkish capital of Ankara on September 14-15, which
will focus on cooperation in fighting organized crime, illegal
immigration and terrorism, as well as in cultural and regional
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Greek diplomatic sources also said that Greek Foreign Minister
George Papandreou will meet his Turkish counterpart, Ismail Cem,
on September 23 on the sidelines of the U.N. general assembly in
New York.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and Turkey, which are both NATO
members, have been strained for decades over territorial disputes,
in particular the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
To ease their tense relations, senior Greek and Turkish
diplomats opened talks in late July in Ankara and Athens,
respectively. Both countries voiced their satisfaction with the
talks, which were described as being held in "a good climate".
</P>
</TEXT>
