<HEADLINE> China's First Arctic Expedition Returns to Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China's first scientific
expedition to the North Pole returned to Shanghai this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This marked the successful conclusion of the government-
sponsored expedition, and now Chinese scientific expeditions have
been to all the seven oceans around the globe.
</P>
<P>
A welcome ceremony featuring colorful banners, flowers, and the
deafening sound of gongs and drums was held at the Port of
Shanghai to greet the returning expedition.
</P>
<P>
The expedition's 124 members aboard the ship Snow Dragon left
Shanghai 71 days ago, and have since traveled some 13,000 nautical
miles and conducted scientific research and investigations over an
area of 400,000 sq km.
</P>
<P>
"We've collected a lot of valuable samples and surveying data,"
said chief scientist Chen Liqi.
</P>
<P>
He said that this expedition has greatly improved the ability
of Chinese scientists to conduct research in the polar region, and
has laid a sound foundation for future research.
</P>
<P>
China has sent out 15 scientific expeditions since 1984, and
the 16th will leave for the South Pole in November.  
</P>
</TEXT>
