<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Government Accepts N.Irish Police Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam said on Thursday the British government
accepted in principle former Hong Kong governor Chris Patten's
proposals for a radical overhaul of Northern Ireland's police
force.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam told a news conference in Northern Ireland capital
Belfast that she had extended to the end of November the period
for debating the proposals, which aim to make the
Protestant-dominated Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC) more
acceptable to the Roman Catholic minority.
</P>
<P>
The Patten Commission on the future of policing in Northern
Ireland, which was set up a year ago under the Good Friday
agreement, has recommended 175 changes to the RUC, including
reducing the size of the RUC from 13,000 to about 8,000 and
renaming the RUC as the Northern Ireland Police Service,
</P>
<P>
The changes also include a new badge, flag, oath of allegiance,
uniform and drive to recruit Catholics into the force.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam encouraged the parties to look closely at the document
and said she had decided to extend the consultation period from
two to three months because of those complaints.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionist Party Thursday responded angrily to plans
to transform the RUC.
</P>
<P>
Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble said the proposals to
change the name of the RUC and take away its flag and badge were
"a gratuitous insult" and predicted the public would reject the
whole report.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein chief negotiator Martin McGuinness said his party
would scrutinize the report to see if it adhered to its
requirements under the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
In London, Prime Minister Tony Blair described the Patten
report on the future of the RUC as the "way forward" for policing
in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged the difficulties both unionist and nationalist
communities would have in accepting some of the proposals.
</P>
<P>
But he urged everyone to take time to digest the detail of the
report.
</P>
<P>
The Patten report was welcomed by the Irish Government as
"thorough and comprehensive".
</P>
<P>
The Irish Government said the recommendations would strengthen
the effectiveness of the police throughout the island of Ireland
by enhancing relations between the police forces on both sides of
the border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
