<HEADLINE> OAU Special Summit Seeks Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIRTE, LIBYA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Participants to an
extraordinary summit of the Organization of African Unity are
expected to sign a declaration that calls for economic integration
before winding up four days of talks later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The declaration is expected to call on member states to push
ahead with the implementation of the 1991 Abuja Treaty that sought
to set up an African Economic Community.
</P>
<P>
The Abuja Treaty provided for a series of pan-Africanist
measures over a period of 30 years, such as higher rates of
economic growth and development, sustained increases in living
standards and investment.
</P>
<P>
However, only a handful of African countries have approached
these goals.
</P>
<P>
The 43 heads of state and government who participated the
summit are also expected to recommend that specific dates be set
for the establishment of a pan-African parliament, a federal
court, a monetary fund and other institutions. A commission would
present the dates to the OAU's next summit in Togo in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
