<HEADLINE> Schroeder Names New German Transport Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to win party
left-wingers' support to Berlin cabinet, German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder on Thursday named Reinhard Klimmt, the outgoing premier
of Saarland State, as his new Minister of Transport and
Construction.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing minister Franz Muentefering will become the SPD's
general secretary to beef up the party's fortunes, Schroeder said
in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Klimmt, 57, was ousted from power in the state election on
Sunday after ruling Saarland for hardly 1 year as successor to
former Finance Minister Oscar Lafontaine.
</P>
<P>
And just like Lafontaine, Klimmt is regarded as the spokesman
of the traditional wing in Germany's ruling Social democratic
Party (SPD). He has been bluntly criticizing Schroeder's
pro-business "new middle line" and the strict fiscal reform plan
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
However, as analysts have pointed out, Schroeder wants to keep
the unity of his party following two defeats in Sunday's
elections. The SPD lost sole control of Saarland and Brandenburg
governments with poor scores in polling.
</P>
<P>
Announcing his choice at a press conference Thursday afternoon,
Schroeder said he would "bundle up all power of the SPD to secure
the program for future."
</P>
<P>
He has picked up Klimmt as Transport Minister because of the
latter's experience in Saarland government, said Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
"It is his experience that will help him tackle the challenges
ahead of us in transport and construction," he said, praising
Klimmt as a "fully qualified politician" and "good team player."
</P>
<P>
And Klimmt's critics on the fiscal reform plan "will not belong
to his future stand as Transport Minister," stressed Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Klimmt also expressed his readiness to compromise with the
party boss Schroeder, saying: "As Transport Minister, I am not
responsible for the fiscal reform."
</P>
<P>
The Chancellor has known his political position well, Klimmt
told the press. He assured Schroeder that he would accept the
decision of majority in the party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
