<HEADLINE> Mozambican Parliament Adopts Resolution on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican parliament Thursday
urged the international community to take measures to end "the
genocidal bloodbath" in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
A resolution passed unanimously by the Assembly of the Republic
noted that the East Timorese people "voted massively for their
national independence" in the referendum held on August 31.
</P>
<P>
But, it said this historic result "unleashed criminal
activities by the enemies of freedom, independence and equality
amongst peoples".
</P>
<P>
The deputies expressed "unconditional solidarity with the
brother people of East Timor, who are the targets of violence,
ethnic cleansing and extermination".
</P>
<P>
They urged the international community and the United Nations
(U.N.) in particular to act immediately to stop the ongoing
genocidal bloodbath, and to guarantee the implementation of the
right to independence that the East Timorese people have so
massively reaffirmed.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly agreed to forward copies of the resolution to U.N.
 Secretary-General Kofi Annan, to the embassies of the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council in Maputo, and to
the Honorary Consul of Indonesia in Mozambique.  
</P>
