<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Rejects Military Intervention in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has rejected
U.N. proposed military intervention in East Timor, U.N. spokesman
Fred Eckhard said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"President B.J. Habibie today told the members of the Security
Council mission visiting Jakarta that he will welcome any form of
international assistance to deal with East Timor except military,
rejecting the Council mission's offer of a multi-national force to
restore law and order to the territory," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The President repeated the assurances that the Indonesian
authorities would get the situation under control," he added.
</P>
<P>
Entering the U.N. headquarters here, U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan also said Indonesia indicated that the martial law is
just taking force in East Timor and that with a bit of time the
Indonesians will be able to bring the situation under control.
</P>
<P>
U.N. personnel in East Timor reported that the situation around
the compound of the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) was "the
quietest" Wednesday since Monday and things "had marginally
improved".
</P>
<P>
However attempts to reach UNAMET's warehouse in the port area
of Dili, the capital, again was halted by anti-independence
militia Thursday as they fired over the head U.N. staff despite
the presence of Indonesian military escort, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's U.N. Ambassador Makarim Wibisono said Thursday
violence in East Timor was subsiding with no more arson or burning
or looting reported and "the conflicting parties have agreed to
stop their action".
</P>
<P>
The five-member Security Council mission is scheduled to meet
the Indonesian military chief on Friday and to visit East Timor on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the U.N. is waiting for the return of the mission to
get the first-hand knowledge about the situation in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
In the Security Council, a closed-door meeting has just ended
and a presidential statement said Council members expressed their
"gravest concern" at the continuing very serious security
situation in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The Council again called on the Indonesian authorities to take
urgent and effective steps to guarantee UNAMET's safety and
security.
</P>
<P>
The statement repeated the Council's stand that if the security
situation does not improve within a very short period of time,
Council members will consider "further action" to help Indonesia
achieve this objective, without specifying the nature of the
action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
