<HEADLINE> Hamas Member Sentenced 26 Life-Imprisonments for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 9 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli military court
Thursday sentenced a member of the Islamic militant group Hamas to
26 consecutive life-imprisonment sentences on conviction of
planning and ordering two serious suicide bombings in downtown
Jerusalem in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The number of life imprisonments given to 24-year-old Ammar
al-Zibben was corresponding to the number of Israelis killed in
the two attacks.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one Israelis and five Hamas suicide bombers were killed
at the explosions at a main open market and a popular pedestrian
mall in the city.
</P>
<P>
Al-Zibben, from the West Bank town of Nablus, was arrested in
January 1998. The indictment said he had served in the Palestinian
National Authority police force while being a member of an
underground Hamas cell.
</P>
<P>
He was also found guilty by the court late last month of other
operations, including producing explosives and shooting at
settlers, Israeli radio reports said.
</P>
<P>
Sentencing for these convictions will be handed down later
this year.
</P>
<P>
Hamas, which opposes the Israeli-Palestinian peace making, has
killed scores of Israelis in a series of attacks it staged in
Israel since the signing of the historic Oslo peace accords in
1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
