<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel released 200 Palestinian political
prisoners early Thursday morning as promised in a new peace deal
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under a revised agreement for the Wye Accord signed last Sunday
in Egyptian Red Sea resort Sharm El Sheikh, Israel, among other
things, should let go 350 Palestinian political prisoners in two
phases. The second batch of 150 will get freedom on October 8.
(BC-Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Interior Minister Habib el-Adli referred
three top police officials in Port Said to a disciplinary council
on Thursday for interrogation for failure to perform their duty
during a visit there by President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Monday, Mubarak was attacked and slightly injured by a
knife-wielding man described as an Islamic fanatic when the
president was riding to a meeting in the Mediterranean port, 180
kilometers northeast of Cairo, at the northern end of the Suez
Canal.
</P>
<P>
The three officers are Port Said Security Director Maj. Gen.
Hassan Abdel Motteleb Othman Jebril, Director of State Security
Investigation Maj. Gen. Abdullah Nasr and Criminal Investigation
Director Brig. Mohammad Sallem Shalan, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported. (BC-Egypt-Police-Interrogation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Officials from Israel's Finance Ministry and
Education Ministry continued their efforts Thursday to find a way
out of a coalition crisis over the governmental funding of
religious schools.
</P>
<P>
The powerful ultra-Orthodox religious party Shas has threatened
to quit the coalition of Prime Minister Ehud Barak if the
government does not transfer 12 million shekels (about 2.85
million U.S. dollars) to its educational networks before the
beginning of the Jewish New Year, which falls on Friday evening.
(BC-Israel-Coalition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
