<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New GA Session to Begin on September 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The 54th session of the
General Assembly (GA) is expected to kick off on September 14,
with Theo-Ben Gurirab, Namibian foreign minister, as the incoming
president, a senior U.N. official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Jin Yongjian, under-secretary-general for General Assembly
affairs and conference services, told a press conference that the
new GA session, also the last one in this century, is scheduled to
open at 3:00 p.m. EST next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On the first day of the GA session, three new members, namely
Kiribati, Nauru and Tonga, will be admitted, thus bringing the
total U.N. Member States to 188, he said.
</P>
<P>
The three countries have been already recommitted by the
Security Council for the new U.N. membership.
</P>
<P>
The general debate will begin on September 20 and last about
two weeks. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan will introduce his
annual report on the work of the Organization before the beginning
of the general debate, he said.
</P>
<P>
"For the general debate of the 54th session, so far 183
delegations have inscribed on the list," he said. In other words,
all Member States, except Yugoslavia and Somalia, have inscribed.
</P>
<P>
"Up to this moment, we expect 40 heads of state and 26 heads of
government, one crown prince to participate in the general
debate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan is expected to take the
floor at the general debate on September 22.
</P>
<P>
"This is a large number of heads of state and heads of
government for a regular session," he said. "This also reflects
the importance Member States attach to the general debate and the
U.N. as a whole."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations will also convene a special session on the
development of small island states on September 27-28, he said.
</P>
<P>
So far, 102 delegations have inscribed for the special session,
he said. "We expect four heads of state and six heads of
government to debate during these two days."
</P>
<P>
For the 54th session, "so far we have 166 items on the
provisional agenda, plus five on the supplementary list," he said.
The General Committee will meet on September 15 to consider all
these items and allocate them to various committees if included in
the official agenda.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly is the main deliberative organ. It is
composed of representatives of all Member States, each of which
has one vote. The GA's regular session usually begins each year in
September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
