<HEADLINE> SADC Should Embrace Global Competition: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Further success of Southern
African Development Community (SADC) countries should depend on
commitment to global competitiveness of individual countries,
Chairman of British Airways said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lord Marshall was delivering a keynote address at the opening
of a two- day Institute of Directors (IoD) convention in Harare.
</P>
<P>
He said the continent has to strengthen itself through forming
trading and economic groups.
</P>
<P>
To attract more investors, a country has to realize that it is
in an increasingly competitive global marketplace, he said.
</P>
<P>
He argued that weaker countries must come together as an area
and improve their competitive effectiveness to avoid being swept
away by globalization.
</P>
<P>
SADC countries must be highly competitive, liberalized and
deregulated to ensure a high level of investment and to face the
challenge of the new millenium, Southern African IoD economist
Graeme Leach added.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the countries must ensure low volatility in
macro-economy, low inflation and low interest rates so that direct
savings go to the private sector. Foreign exchange stability is
also crucial. The people must be given the right incentives and
trusted".
</P>
<P>
The IoD convention is co-sponsored by the IoD Zimbabwe and the
IoD in Southern Africa, with the participants coming from
companies, parastatals and non-governmental organizations,
government departments and professional organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
