<HEADLINE> Chirac Opens Exhibition of Works of Chardin in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
opened Thursday evening an exhibition of the great 18th century
French realist painter Jean-Baptiste Simeon Chardin (1699-1779) at
the Grand Palais Museum in Paris.
</P>
<P>
About 100 works of Chardin are displayed and they will move on
to Dusseldorf, Germany, after November 22. They will also be
displayed in London and New York next year.
</P>
<P>
The head of the French luxury industrial group LVMH, Bernard
Arnault, has financially sponsored the exhibition and the
president of the Louvre Museum Pierre Rosenberg serves as the
commissioner of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Among the displayed works of Chardin is "The Little Girl Who
Plays by Jumping" depicting a lovely doll, which was painted in
1737 soon after the death of Chardin's own daughter.
</P>
<P>
The painting, which once belonged to Russian Empress Catherine
the Great, was later bought by the Rothschild family.
</P>
<P>
Little known in the 19th century, Chardin was admired in the
20th century by both conservative painters and those of socialist
realism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0059 </DOCNO>
