<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Appeals to EU, NATO to Resume Traffic on Danube </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government
Thursday appealed to the European Union (EU) and NATO member
countries for the deblocking the Danubean navigable channel, the
official Rompres news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Transport Traian Basescu stressed it was the EU and
NATO countries' responsibility to resume traffic on the Danube,
which has been stopped due to the bombing of the bridges during
the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing a paradoxical situation now, viz., the EU
imposed an embargo against Yugoslavia, which we are backing up,
but it practically turned, by its effects, into an embargo on the
Romanian fleet to sail on the Danube," complained the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The EU must ponder it well that Romania is not
subject to the embargo and that it is the fate of a state against
which an embargo was imposed."
</P>
<P>
Basescu said that the ministry he leads approved a three-way
meeting among the Ukrainian, Bulgarian and Romanian shipowners to
be held in Romania, to approach the issue of traffic on the Danube
and that of clearing the navigable channel.
</P>
<P>
Romanian shipowners and port operators have blocked the traffic
on the Danube for three days starting Monday, in a protest against
the EU refusal to free the navigable channel in the area of the
three bridges destroyed in Serbian Novi Sad during the war.
</P>
<P>
Blocking the Danube by shipowners is a consequence of the fact
that Romania has not felt any positive effects of the
international oil embargo on Yugoslavia, Prime Minister Radu
Vasile said.
</P>
<P>
"Romania and the Romanian government fulfilled their
obligations 100 percent" in terms of the oil embargo as well as
other factors established by the EU and NATO, Vasile added.
</P>
<P>
"Despite this fact, Romania has not experienced any positive
effects of such a firm and precise attitude, underlined by all EU
and NATO official representatives," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Romanian companies of river navigation have sustained losses of
almost 1.3 million U.S. dollars a month, as a result of the
conflict in Yugoslavia and of the delay in unblocking the traffic
on the Danube. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
