<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corporate Earnings Push Europe's Markets Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Europe's main stock markets
managed to hold on to modest gains at the close Thursday with
Paris leading the way at a record high close.
</P>
<P>
London's benchmark FTSE index finished little changes on the
day as the gains in the oil sector were offset by softer
pharmaceuticals and mixed telecoms.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 closed 7 points higher at 6,260.6, having ranged
between 6,271.2 and 6,242.3. Provisional volume in London was 943
million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
The UK's oil majors were the main gainers on the day, joined by
Cable &AMP; Wireless in positive moves. BP Amoco and Shell jumped 2.4
percent and 3.4 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt closed 36 points higher at 5,436.86,
a rise of 0.7 percent, lifted by comments from Wim Duisenberg,
president of the European Central Bank, who said he sees sustained
growth and price stability in the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
Leading French shares rose on the day to help Paris' benchmark
Cac-40 index rise 0.3 percent to 4,693, its highest ever closing
level.
</P>
<P>
The index was buoyed by strong first-half results from
tire-maker Michelin, which saw its shares surge 11 percent to 47.3
euros. 
</P>
</TEXT>
