<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Concerned Over Incidents on Border With India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Friday summoned
India's acting High Commissioner Hamid Ali Rao to the Foreign
Ministry to hear Dhaka's grave concern over a series of incidents
which took place in the past few months along the border with
India.
</P>
<P>
The Indian envoy was told that those border incidents
contributed to an undesirable build-up of tension in the border
areas, a senior Foreign Ministry official told the media.
</P>
<P>
The incidents involve areas termed as adverse possessions,
which have been in existence since 1947, the official said, adding
that a special dispensation was made with regard to these areas in
the 1947 border agreement with a provision for maintaining the
status quo until their eventual transfer in accordance with the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The official said that during the past few months, a group of
Indian nationals supported by the Indian Border Security Forces
(BSF) have sought to plow a stretch of land under such adverse
possessions of Bangladesh. On the other hand, when Bangladeshi
nationals were engaged in plowing the same land, the BSF warned
them of serious consequences unless they leave the place.
</P>
<P>
The official said the trend was quite evident that there was a
discernible effort on the part of the Indian field officials to
change the status quo in clear violation of the 1975 Border
Guidelines. At least it could be concluded that the BSF field
officials were inclined not to recognize the status of adverse
possessions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is an undesirable development," he added.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the important strides made in our bilateral
relations during the past few years, it is felt that greater
efforts must be made to maintain peace and tranquillity in the
border areas so that such border incidents are not allowed to
detract from the close relations between the two countries," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
