<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China's New Policies Expected to Draw More Overseas Funds (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- China has just issued a series
of important preferential policies to further encourage overseas
investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
Experts say these policies, many of which are much bolder than
previous ones, will lay a sound foundation for China's better
utilization of overseas capital in the coming century.
</P>
<P>
The new policies, announced this week by a senior Chinese
official at the ongoing Third China Fair for International
Investment and Trade, include encouraging overseas investors to
engage in technology development and innovation by offering tax
cuts or exemptions, allowing qualified overseas-funded businesses
to issue both A-shares, which are available only to domestic
investors, and B-shares reserved for overseas investors, and
easing restrictions on overseas investors in joint ventures in the
central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
Analysts note that these policies have been released amid the
first downward trend in both the country's contractual overseas
investment and its actual use of overseas funds during the first
half this year.
</P>
<P>
They said these new policies are intended not only to check the
current downturn in overseas investment, but also to foster an
open economy to achieve a sustained and rapid economic growth in
the next century.
</P>
<P>
Ma Xiuhong, assistant minister of the Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), said that attracting overseas
investment in technology development and innovation promotion will
be conducive to upgrading domestic industries.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Ma said, advanced technology and management expertise
brought by overseas investors will help China to improve the
quality of its economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"Directing overseas investment to the central and western areas
is expected to bring about a balanced development of the national
economy," Ma added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China's New Policies Expected to Draw More Overseas Funds (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since 1978, when the reform and opening up policies were
introduced, China has maintained a sustained and rapid economic
growth, in which overseas investment has played a role.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that China has ranked second in the world
in utilizing of overseas funds for six years, second only to the
United States. There are now 334,000 overseas-funded businesses
in China, with combined overseas capital actually used standing at
290 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
These enterprises employ 18 million people, and last year
contributed 44 percent to China's total exports, and 14.4 percent
to the country's tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
This year, however, the number of newly approved overseas-
funded enterprises, and the volume of committed and actually used
overseas funds, have all decreased, with actual overseas
investment reaching only 21.5 billion U.S. dollars during the
January-July period, down 10 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute this downturn to the negative impact of the
Asian financial crisis and the change of mode in international
investment from direct investment to acquisitions and mergers.
</P>
<P>
Sun Guangxiang, MOFTEC's vice minister, said that China must
take active measures to attract more overseas investment in order
to maintain a sustained, rapid and healthy economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"As a developing country, China is still suffering from a
severe shortage of funds," Sun added.
</P>
<P>
To draw an appropriate amount of overseas funds, experts note,
it is sensible to make some adjustments to related policies.
</P>
<P>
A multinational CEO attending the fair said that China is now
creating a more favorable business environment and will surely
attract an increasing number of overseas investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
