<HEADLINE> At Least 3 Killed in Fresh Clash in Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- At least three persons were
killed and 12 others injured in a fresh outbreak of communal clash
in Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku province, on Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to the Antara News Agency, security forces aimed
their guns at rioters after firing a series of warning shots. The
mob ignored the warning shots and even tried to break through the
security cordon by throwing two hand-made bombs at the security
troops.
</P>
<P>
The security forces eventually frustrated the mob's attempt to
enter the Maluku gubernatorial offices compound.
</P>
<P>
The security troops also had to fire warning shots to disperse
the rioters in the Batumerah and Batugantung areas in the city,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ambon and several other islands in Maluku province have been
the scene of violent clashes between Muslims and Christian groups
since mid-January this year.
</P>
<P>
Local religious figures, along with the military, had tried to
gwvnpmlbrrcowtvcnxrnlqkglcrlrcc
reconcile the warring camps but clashes broke out again in
mid-July, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The unrest in July claimed dozens of lives, injured an even
bigger number of people and caused hundreds of residents to flee
their homes.
</P>
<P>
Most of Indonesia's 202 million people are Muslims, but Maluku
is a predominantly Christian province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
