<HEADLINE> Vialli: Keegan Part-time Role to Blame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- English premier league soccer
club Chelsea manager Gianluca Vialli reckons a "messy" handover
from Glenn Hoddle to Kevin Keegan is to blame for the struggle to
qualify for Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
England need Sweden to beat Poland if they are to make the play-
offs in the wake of Wednesday's goalless draw with the Poles in
Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
Chelsea boss Vialli believes the uncertainty created when
Keegan initially agreed to succeed Hoddle for just three games did
not help prospects of qualification.
</P>
<P>
Keegan committed himself to three years in charge of England
after his first two matches -- a 3-1 Euro 2000 victory over Poland
and a 1-1 draw with Hungary.
</P>
<P>
But Vialli believes the damage had been done. He said: "The
problem was that it was a bit of a mess when the manager was
changed."
</P>
<P>
"Kevin Keegan took over but nobody knew whether he was going to
stay for one match or two or until the end of the season or for
longer."
</P>
<P>
"It was at that stage that England lost their qualification,
because of all the confusion," Vialli told the Daily Mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
