<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang: Visit to Australia Attains Desired Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRNS, Australia, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President
Jiang Zemin said here Friday that his five-day visit to Australia
has attained the desired goal.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that during the visit, he met Australian Governor-
General William Patrick Deane and exchanged views with Prime
Minister John Howard on bilateral relations, as well as
international and regional issues of common interest, which
produced positive and constructive results.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks in his toast at an informal barbecue
dinner hosted in his honor by Nick Minchin, Australian Minister
for Industry, Science and Resources.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that in his talks with Howard, both of them
expressed satisfaction over and highly evaluated the progress made
in the development of China-Australia relations since the
establishment of the diplomatic ties between the two countries 27
years ago.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to foster a 21st-century-oriented relationship of
long-term stability, healthy development and all-round cooperation
between China and Australia. And to this end, top leaders and
foreign ministers from both sides will meet once each year
regularly, Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiang, China and Australia will make best use of
the complementarity between their economies and further tap the
potential in their economic and trade cooperation. They will also
enhance collaboration in consular affairs, mining, law enforcement,
science and technology, as well as education, while continuing to
open up new areas of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed that differences between China and Australia
in political system, history, culture and tradition are by no
means obstacles to the development of the friendly relations and
cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
No clash of fundamental interest exists between China and
Australia, Jiang noted, adding that both of them, being important
countries in the Asia-Pacific region, have extensive common
interests and shoulder common responsibilities in safeguarding
world peace and stability and in promoting regional economic
prosperity and development.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said Howard and he expressed their readiness to step up
consultation and cooperation within international and regional
organizations and on major international and regional issues. They
also agreed to make efforts to promote the establishment of a fair
and equitable international economic and financial order.
</P>
<P>
Minchin, in his speech, said the people of Australia feel
honored to welcome a Chinese head of state to Australia for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
As the Chinese President is leaving for Auckland of New Zealand
Saturday to attend the 7th Informal Meeting of leaders of Asia-
Pacific Economic Cooperation, he wished Jiang's trip a full
success.
</P>
<P>
Jiang arrived in Cairns earlier Friday. Cairns is the last leg
of his state visit to Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0078 </DOCNO>
