<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT September 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Rescuers have pulled out 69 bodies from the rubble of
an apartment building ripped apart by a powerful explosion early
Thursday in southeastern Moscow, Mayor Yuri Luzhkov said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rescue efforts are continuing as over 50 people are still
believed to be under the debris, but not a single survivor had
been spotted for over 20 hours, the Itar-Tass news agency said.
Pockets of fire in the basements, smoke and steaming have hampered
the rescuers. (Russia-Explosion-Death Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Seven more people have been killed and five others
injured in the latest of an unprecedented surge of road accidents.
</P>
<P>
The accident took place Thursday on a road near the tourist
resort of Luxor, 550 kilometers south of Cairo, when a truck
crashed into a mini-bus, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported
on Friday. (Egypt-Road Accident)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- The Palestinian side expected the Israeli government to
fully and timely implement the newly signed peace accord to move
the Mideast peace process forward,said a senior Palestinian
official here Friday.
</P>
<P>
After Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's approval of the
redeployment maps delivered to him by the Israeli side, his
political advisor Nabil Abu rdeineh told reporters that Arafat
approved the maps after studying them carefully with his military
advisors.(Gaza-Arafat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AUCKLAND -- Ministers attending the 11th Ministerial Meeting of
the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum have approved
measures for moving more rapidly toward paperless trading
throughout the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement adopted at the end of the two-day ministerial
meeting Friday said the ministers accorded high priority to a
number of targets for achieving paperless trading, where possible,
by 2005 for developed APEC member economies and 2010 for
developing ones. (APEC-E-Commerce)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Former South African President Nelson Mandela
was vindicated on Friday by the country's top court when it
reversed an earlier defeat for the government in a controversial
case over rugby.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court overturned the High Court victory of
the South African Rugby Football Union (Sarfu), which had
maintained that Mandela did not give due consideration when he
appointed a commission to investigate the white-dominated sport,
according to a report by the South African Press Association(SAPA).
(SAfrica-Court-Former President) 
</P>
</TEXT>
