<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Refutes U.S. Remarks on Religious Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese Foreign
Ministry's spokeswoman Phan Thuy Thanh Friday refuted U.S. remarks
about its religious situation, arguing that religious believers in
Vietnam enjoy equality and are free to practice their religions.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about Vietnam's reaction to U.S.
Department of State remarks on the religious situation in Vietnam,
Thanh said the allegation that the United States reserves the
right to judge other countries' religious situation runs counter
to the fundamental principles of international law.
</P>
<P>
"Vietnam is a country of different religions and beliefs,"
Thanh said, affirming that Vietnam has been always respecting
religious freedom and non-religious freedom and has never
prevented any religious activities.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally," she added, "any religion belongs to a certain
community and a certain nation. So, the religious believers must
observe the laws of their nation while practicing religions."
</P>
</TEXT>
