<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Dip Temporary: Economic Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
assured the public Friday that the slight dip of the peso against
the greenback is a temporary effect of the political crisis in
East Timor, saying the "fundamental strength" of the peso is under
control.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu pointed out that the country
continues to enjoy an export boom which accounts for most of the
country's dollar inflow, backed by the what he called the
ever-reliable remittances from Filipino migrant workers,
Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Observers said developments in Thailand and Indonesia continued
to provide a reason for the bashing of the peso, which reached as
low as 40.32 against the U.S. dollar Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I think that our people should not be alarmed by the slight
dip in the peso because the currency's fundamental strength is
under our control," Espiritu said.
</P>
<P>
"Our reserve is sufficient. Our export is also rising, which
comprises the bulk of our dollar inflows. The remittance of our
countrymen abroad also continues to flow in," he added.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu noted the threat of the International Monetary Fund to
withdraw support for Indonesia should it fail to address the
problem in East Timor has dealt a blow to the stability of some
currencies in the region.
</P>
<P>
He added that the East Timor crisis has also affected the Thai
baht whose decline he said was sharper than the peso.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu urged traders and other quarters engaged in dollar
trading not to take advantage of the situation, noting that the
central bank is keeping a close watch over their activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
