<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Supports Initiatives for Arab Unity: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf said on Friday his country supports any ideas and
initiatives aimed at closing Arab ranks at the upcoming meeting of
Arab foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
"Any efforts aimed at achieving Arab unity should be well
studied and well probed in a bid to reach a balanced and
reasonable formula for reconciliation," Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf
said upon arrival in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
"We must study the ideas on the basis of sincere and honest
participation," al-Sahhaf told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official will chair the two-day 112th session of the
Arab League Foreign Ministers Council, scheduled on Sunday and
Monday, under the rotational system.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf said he has planned to meet with a number of his
counterparts on the sidelines of the meetings to seek ways of
improving bilateral ties and Arab reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
He is to meet with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on
Saturday to discuss the agenda of the upcoming foreign ministers'
meeting, which includes the Iraqi issue, and bilateral relations,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf's remarks followed calls by Arab League Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid that Iraq use its chairmanship of the
meeting as a means to resolve its differences with other Arab
countries, and to cooperate with an Arab committee set up during
the last meeting of Arab foreign ministers in January to help get
U.N. sanctions on Iraq lifted.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has refused to recognize the committee or cooperate with
it unless it becomes a member.
</P>
<P>
But al-Sahhaf's comments Friday suggested that Iraq may now
take a more flexible stand than it did at the last league
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will deal "positively" with any initiatives aimed at
ironing out the differences between it and other Arab countries,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf walked out of January's final meeting after the
foreign ministers failed to strongly condemn the sanctions and the
U.S.-British airstrikes on his country.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council imposed the economic
sanctions on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched four days of airstrikes in
December against Iraq for what the western allies denounced as
Baghdad's failure to comply with the U.N. Security Council
resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
