<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Urged to Repatriate Filipinos in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Senate President
Blas Ople on Friday called on the government to immediately
repatriate the remaining Filipinos, particularly priests and nuns,
in the violence-torn East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, Ople said the Philippine
Armed Forces should immediately send a plane to East Timor for the
possible evacuation of the priests and nuns, one of whom has
reportedly been killed by military men.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the violent strike that is tearing that territory
apart, we should evacuate these Filipino priests and nuns," he
said, adding that their lives and safety may be further imperiled
due to the military takeover in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
But Ople said the evacuation of the Filipinos still needs prior
clearance from the Indonesian government and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Press reports quoted an unidentified Philippine embassy staff
in Jakarta, Indonesia, as saying Filipino missionaries have
already been informed of their planned evacuation, but had showed
reluctance to leave the territory.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that while Filipino missionaries doing
humanitarian work in the territory are not the "targets" of
militia groups, they may be subjected to "incidental dangers" such
as explosions and street violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
