<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton, citing "gross abuses" in East Timor,moved
Thursday to isolate Indonesia by cutting off U.S. military ties,
and the International Monetary Fund effectively suspended its
multibillion-dollar lending program to the Southeast Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Federal employees, including about 250,000 civil
servants iln the Washington area, would receive a 4.8 percent pay
increase this January under an agreement reached Thursday by House
and Senate negotiators. It would amount to the largest salary
boost since 1981.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton demanded that Indonesia invite an
international peacekeeping force into East Timor if the Indonesian
military is unable to end the viaolence that has swept the
province since it voted for independence. He also ordered the
Pentagon to suspend formal contacts with the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
-- Israel released 199 palestinian prisoners in the first
concrete step in the revival of the Israeli-Palestinian peace
effort.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The CIA warned that the ballistic-missile threat to the U.S.
by rogue states is growing quickly, citing in particular North
Korea. The report increases the likelihood that the White House
will proceed with a missile-defense program.
</P>
<P>
-- The White House announced a 15 million dollars federal gun-
buyback program. The plan will give local police departments up to
500,000 dollars to buy guns in and around public housing projects
and then destroy the weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
