<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan: From Poor Island to Largest SEZ (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hainan's GDP reached 43.8 billion yuan last year, five times
that of 1988, the year the Hainan Special Economic Zone was
established.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, Hainan became the fifth special economic zone, with
more profitable and open policies, and began to carry out many
projects in building, real estate, tropical cash crops, and
tourism.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the 30-sq-km development zone of Yangpu was set up in
Hainan by a Hongkong-based company, and that same year Hainan's
per capita GDP reached 2,113 yuan, surpassing the national average.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, overseas funds used in the province was 200 US.
dollars per capita, greater than the provinces of Guangdong and
Fujian, and just behind Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Hainan opened the country's first cooperation
investment project in the field of ocean petroleum and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 11 years, the province's infrastructure
construction has attracted a total of 8.65 billion US dollars, and
the province's import and export value has increased from 300
million to 2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Now, more than 8,600 overseas-funded enterprises are doing
business on the island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
