<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan: From Poor Island to Largest SEZ (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 10 (Xinhua) -- South China's Hainan Province,
the country's largest special economic zone (SEZ), has now enjoyed
twenty years of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"I never thought Hainan could become so modern and developed,"
said Xing Ming, who was born and grew up in Haikou, capital of
this southernmost island province.
</P>
<P>
"Twenty years ago, my dream was to leave the city -- my poor
hometown -- and work in the metropolis of Guangzhou in Guangdong
Province," Xing said. "Compared with Guangzhou, Haikou was just
like a rural area, the highest building in the city was only six
storeys and there were almost no road construction sites or
telecommunication facilities."
</P>
<P>
"But now, hundreds of thousands of people across the country
would like to live and work on the island, and it has also become
appealing to both domestic and overseas investors," said Xing, who
runs an Internet company in Haikou.
</P>
<P>
With booming economic growth, Hainan has opened airports in
Haikou and the port city of Sanya, and an expressway between the
two cities. Moreover, the province has initiated a series of
transportation construction projects, including the Yuehai railway
connecting Hainan and the mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
