<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Story of a Folk Doctor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: This year is the 50th anniversary of the People'
s Republic of China. Xinhua News Agency is releasing 50 stories on
Chinese men and women, young and old, to illustrate the changes
that have taken place in China over the past half century. These
people will describe their lives and how they fit into the changes
in the motherland. This is the 21st story in the series.
</P>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- After exploring the
applications of herbal medicines for several decades, Chinese folk
doctor Lai Chunrong was able to advance theory in the field and
has become known as the "King of Herbal Medicine."
</P>
<P>
Born in 1951 in Hangzhou, capital of east China's Zhejiang
Province, Lai Chunrong was a diligent student at school and his
lifelong ambition was to become a writer.
</P>
<P>
But recurrent illnesses in Lai's family radically changed his
life. Lai's grandmother contracted skin cancer and his father then
died from tuberculosis. In deep grief, Lai vowed to go into
medicine to find cures for diseases.
</P>
<P>
Lai traveled widely in Zhejiang, and then went to east China's
Fujian Province and southwest China's Sichuan Province to learn
from renowned doctors of Chinese traditional medicine. He
eventually became knowledgeable enough to curing illnesses such as
leukemia and kidney diseases.
</P>
<P>
Lai practiced Chinese traditional medicine at home and abroad
while gaining increased popularity in the mainland of China, Hong
Kong, Singapore, Malaysia, and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
While practicing traditional medicine, Lai also devoted himself
to researching the applications of herbal medicines, and came up
with many original theories.
</P>
<P>
Lai said a competent doctor of Chinese traditional should be
able to discern the nature and function of different herbs by
paying attention to the environment for the growth of herbs, and
to apply them wisely in accordance with the nature of that
environment.
</P>
<P>
Lai also put forward the theory that differences may also exist
in herbs of the exact same kind due to differing environments, and
that these herbs have their own life cycles and should be
collected in their prime for the best results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
