<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Mourn Victims of Blasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin on Friday declared next Monday a day of mourning
for the victims killed in the blasts in Moscow and Buinaksk of
Daghestan.
</P>
<P>
As Putin addressed on television, rescue efforts were
continuing at the site of a powerful blast that ripped apart a
nine-story apartment building Wednesday night in southeast Moscow
where 75 bodies have been pulled out from under the rubble.
</P>
<P>
The victims included of 32 women, five little girls, 34 men and
three little boys. The death toll is expected to continue rising
as rescuers excavate more bodies from the debris.
</P>
<P>
"Death of people is always a tragedy, whatever its cause,"
Putin said, adding that authorities are looking "whether it was
negligence, criminal carelessness in handling explosive substances
or a terrorist act."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov said it was almost certain
the blast was caused by an explosive device.
</P>
<P>
The timing of the blast, at 23:39:58 Wednesday night, also
suggested that it was an act of terror, the Itar-Tass news agency
quoted Luzhkov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Early Friday, Putin approved a plan to prevent acts of
terrorism in Russia and Moscow proposed by the Federal Security
Service (FSB) and the Interior Ministry, FSB Director Nikolai
Patrushev said.
</P>
<P>
According to Patrushev, new information about the causes of the
Moscow explosion appeared at 23:00 Thursday -- traces of hexogen
and TNT were discovered at the site which proves that the
explosion was not accidental.
</P>
<P>
However, he said this scenario should not become predominant
and all other possibilities should also be checked, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We are interested in public support and people have actively
responded. The survivors are receiving energetic help and
assistance is being given to investigators," Patrushev said.
</P>
<P>
He said law enforcement bodies are getting numerous calls form
people willing to report information related to the explosion.
</P>
<P>
An anonymous caller with a Caucasus accent told Interfax
Thursday that the apartment explosion and a Saturday night bomb
blast in Buinaksk, Daghestan, were in response to Russia's
military campaign against Islamic rebels in the southern territory
of the republic bordering the breakaway Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The explosion in Buinaksk, Daghestan, believed to be staged by
Islamic militants, killed more than 60 people when a five-story
residential building was demolished by a car bomb. 
</P>
</TEXT>
