<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Denies Intention to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Friday denied that he intends to resign and delegate his
administrative tasks to a number of ministers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to ulemas from Jakarta and its environs here, Habibie
said he was surprised when an ambassador from a friendly country
asked him if he intends to quit.
</P>
<P>
The head of state said he knew nothing about the rumor.
</P>
<P>
He added that everything is under control and that he also pays
attention to the economic development in East Timor and other
Indonesian provinces.
</P>
<P>
Speculation was fueled by Habibie's sudden cancellation on
Wednesday of all out-of-town trips, including one to New Zealand
to attend the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) informal
leaders' meeting.
</P>
<P>
Habibie told the ulemas that the government will not sacrifice
the 210 million people of Indonesia only for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, when opening a forum on the eradication of HIV/AIDS
here Friday, Habibie said the East Timor issue should not be
politically exploited at the expense of the people and integration
fighters in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that East Timor is different from Indonesia's
other provinces.
</P>
<P>
Despite East Timor's 24-year integration with Indonesia, he
said, the integration process has never been acknowledged by the
international community and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The government's commitment is obvious -- that it will
cooperate with the United Nations to cope with all problems (in
East Timor) during the transition (period)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Habibie said he was going to submit a report on the East Timor
issue to the upcoming general session of the People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR).
</P>
<P>
Indonesia will hand the East Timor issue to the United Nations
after the general session of the MPR in November, Habibie said,
adding that the country, in stages, will withdraw its security and
government personnel from the strife-torn territory.
</P>
<P>
In the August 30 direct autonomy ballot, 78.5 percent of East
Timorese voters favored independence, instead of wide-ranging
autonomy proposed by the Indonesian government in January this
year.
</P>
<P>
But, clashes between pro-integration and pro-independence
groups have taken place in East Timor since the announcement of
the ballot results on September 4, resulting in more than 100
deaths.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government on Tuesday placed East Timor under
martial law in face of escalating violence.
</P>
<P>
Habibie said the government was compelled to impose a state of
military emergency in East Timor as the situation went beyond
control after the announcement of the ballot result.
</P>
<P>
He said he would keep in touch with U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan to inform him and the international community about the
measures being taken in East Timor by the Indonesian government.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
