<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers Call for Strengthening Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ministers attending the 11th
Ministerial Meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) forum have strongly underlined the importance of working
together to strengthen markets in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement adopted at the end of the two-day ministerial
meeting Friday said the ministers agreed to a "road map" that sets
out future work of APEC to strengthen markets in the region.
</P>
<P>
Strengthening markets is one of the three themes of the 7th
informal meeting of APEC leaders following the ministerial
meeting, with the other two themes being "expanding opportunities
for business around the region" and "broadening support for APEC."
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued Friday, Lockwood Smith, chairman of
the APEC ministerial meeting and New Zealand minister for
international trade, said APEC ministers agreed that a durable
recovery and a return to sustained economic growth will require
ongoing commitment to broader economic reform for strengthening
markets, in addition to trade and investment liberalization.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers also recognize that there is a need now to bring
together APEC's work across key areas such as trade and
investment, competition and regulatory reform, economic and
corporate governance, trade facilitation and efforts to reduce
administrative compliance costs on business," he said.
</P>
<P>
The market-strengthening initiative provides such an approach,
according to Smith.
</P>
<P>
The two-day ministerial meeting was in preparation for the 7th
informal meeting of APEC leaders scheduled for September 12 and 13
in Auckland, the largest city of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
APEC was established in 1989 in response to the growing
interdependence among Asia-Pacific economies. It is a grouping of
21 regional economies set up to improve the stability, security
and prosperity of its peoples.
</P>
<P>
It now groups Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, China's
Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua
New Guinea, Peru, the Philippines, Russia, Singapore, South Korea,
Chinese Taipei, Thailand, the United States and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
