<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strives to Become  Major Economic Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- In the past five decades,
China's drive to become a major economic power has succeeded to
the extent that the country is now the seventh largest economy in
the world.
</P>
<P>
According to forecasts by international groups such as the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD),
China will grow into one of the world's top economic powers in the
first 25 years of the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
In the first three decades after New China was founded in 1949,
the nation had an average annual economic growth rate of 6.1
percent a year, far lower than that of Asia's "four dragon"
economies -- Singapore, Korea, Thailand and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Since China began reform and opening up to the outside world in
1979, the economic growth rate has jumped to 9.8 percent a year on
average, 7.3 percentage points higher than that of the developed
countries, and 4.8 percent higher than that of the developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
As China became one of the largest producer of major industrial
and agricultural products in the world, its scientific,
educational and public health levels have reached the world's
upper-middle standard. The people of China now are advancing from
a sufficient life to a comfortable life, as the country plays an
increasingly important role in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, China relied on soft loans from the former Soviet
Union as the major source of foreign investment. During the period
from the 1960s to the end of the 1970s, China had acquired only a
limited amount of foreign fund by attracting bank deposits from
Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
By 1978, China's foreign exchange reserve was only 170 million
US dollars. After two decades of reform and opening up, this
amount increased to the second largest in the world, while income
from international tourism grew to the seventh largest.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, China has been the second largest destination of
international investment, following the United States.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, China's exports accounted for only 0.75 percent and
imports for only 0.81 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China became the ninth largest exporting nation, with
export value accounting for 3.4 percent and import value accounted
for 2.5 percent of the world's total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Vice-Chairman Confident of Macao's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ma Man Kei, vice-chairman of
the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC), Friday expressed his confidence
in a brighter future of Macao after its return to China on
December 20 this year.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua just before the 100-day countdown
of Macao's return to China, Ma said Macao's return is of great
significance to the Chinese nation and the international community.
</P>
<P>
It will signify the end of foreign occupation of Chinese
territory, and will also set an example for the ultimate
reunification of the country with its implementation of the "one
country, two systems" principle, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ma, who has lived in Macao for over half a century, said Macao
people are quite delighted with the return, which demonstrates
that China has become stronger and more prosperous after the
founding of the People's Republic of China, especially since the
reform and opening-up policy was launched 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law of the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR)
has won common recognition in the community, Ma said. He expressed
the belief that the law will surely be carried out smoothly in
Macao after its return.
</P>
<P>
Looking forward to the future, Ma stressed that Macao people
must continue to promote their patriotic tradition and that the
Macao SAR government will firmly observe the one-China principle
on the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Under the "one country, two systems" principle, Macao will
actively continue its exchanges with the outside world and work
hard to serve as a bridge between the mainland and Taiwan, Ma said.
</P>
</TEXT>
