<HEADLINE> Toronto International Film Festival Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Toronto International Film
Festival opened late Thursday, local press reported.
</P>
<P>
During the 10-day event, which ends on September 18, more than
300 films from 52 countries will be projected.
</P>
<P>
Dominating the 24th annual film festival are 171 international
feature films, including 14 Canadian films, of which one by
Canadian director Atom Egoyan was screened at the opening day.
</P>
<P>
The event has been described as "the world's second most
important after Cannes" by American film critic Roger Ebert, local
media said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Although Cannes is still larger, Toronto is more useful and
more important certainly to North America," Ebert was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of film stars are expected in Canada's most populous
city, including Ralph Fiennes, Robin Williams and Susan Sarandon.
</P>
<P>
Compared with Cannes, Venice and Montreal, Toronto is market
oriented without jury to vote on awards for specific international
films.
</P>
<P>
The box office reported a record income of 1.9 million Canadian
dollars (about 1.3 million U.S. dollars) last year, with the city
services netting another 48 million (about 3.3 million dollars)
during the festival. 
</P>
