<HEADLINE> Nigerian Air Force Sells Jets on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Air Force has gone
to the internet to attract bids for its retired combat and
transport aircraft in order to get the best bargain in the world
second-hand military aviation market.
</P>
<P>
The move is to "have the best return for these equipment"
through competitive bidding, the Guardian newspaper Friday quoted
Chief of Air Staff, Air Vice Marshal Isaac Alfa, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some of the aircraft already posted on the internet are the Mig
15, 17 and 21 series, the Sepecat Jaguar, the G-Triple Two (G222),
 Scottish Bulldog, the Fokker 27 Maritime Hercules, the (Dor)
Do-128-6 and the MBB (Bolkow) BO-105. The American 300-C training
helicopter which uses ave-gas is also included.
</P>
<P>
The air force chief had earlier said in the country's western
Niger State, that the force was considering the procurement of new
combat jets. They include the Mig 29 Fulcrum, the Lockheed F-16
Fighting Falcon, and French Rassault MIRAGE 2000-5.
</P>
<P>
The other two aircraft being considered are the Swedish J-39
Saab GRIDDEN and the Sukhoi Su-35.
</P>
<P>
Presidency sources told The Guardian newspaper that apart from
disposing,

reactivation and procurement of new platform, government was also
considering retrofit programs for the air force.  
</P>
</TEXT>
