<HEADLINE> UWCC Promotes TDMA Technology in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking official from
the US-based Universal Wireless Communications Consortium (UWCC)
said today the UWCC hopes to cooperate with China in the future to
help China develop its "third generation" wireless
telecommunication technology.
</P>
<P>
Sheila Mickool, President of the UWCC, said at today's news
conference that the UWCC aims to offer the best solutions for the
needs of China's growing telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
The UWCC, set up in 1996, is a non-profit industry organization
of over 100 telecommunication carriers and vendors supporting TDMA
(Time Division Multiple Access) and WIN (Wireless Intelligent
Network) technology standards. The purpose of this cooperative is
to promote TDMA/WIN as an integrated global wireless
communications technology in the "third generation"
telecommunication era.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 20 million cellular phone subscribers.
The cell phone network predominately utilizes GSM standard,
considered second generation standard technology.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for the switch to a third generation level,
available in the next few years, China has agreed to open the
market up to multiple standards.
</P>
<P>
One of the advantages of TDMA lies in its future inter-
operability with GSM, which is the chief telecommunication
standard employed in China, said Mickool.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from the UWCC has been in China this week and has
held talks with officials and firms from the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
