<HEADLINE> China's Crusade Against Prostitution, Gambling Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese police have been
successful in the latest nationwide crusade against prostitution
and gambling, launched by the Ministry of Public Security in mid-
August, a senior police officer said here today.
</P>
<P>
Police in Shantou, a city in south China's Guangdong Province,
inspected some 1,900 public recreational places, including hotels,
massage parlors, and hair salons.
</P>
<P>
Police solved more than 300 related cases and shut down 21
recreational places for conducting illegal business, confiscating
3.26 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A major gambling ring was infiltrated by police in Guangzhou,
capital of Guangdong Province. According to police sources, the
suspects had received up to 11 million yuan in bets and took in
profit of more than seven million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Police units in Zibo city of east China's Shandong Province
have held training classes for 10,000 employees working in
nightclubs and similar recreational places, in an effort to
improve their awareness of the law.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai police intensified inspections on major streets and
hotels, seizing a total of 227 criminal suspects in a two-week
anti-prostitution action.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the crusade, police units across China
have smashed a number of criminal rings, which organized, forced
or induced women to provide sexual services, the police officer
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
