<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder of Chinese City Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, China, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese City Games
was inaugurated in 1988 and has been held every four years as
athletes only under 20 are eligible for the national meet.
Following are backgrounders of the Games:
</P>
<P>
First City Games:
</P>
<P>
Held in both Jinan and Zibo, Shandong province from October 23
to November 2 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,332 athletes from 42 delegations competed in 12
sports of athletics, swimming, weightlifting, shooting, wrestling,
judo, soccer, basketball, volleyball, badminton, table tennis and
gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
One world record was broken, and three Asian records were
surpassed.
</P>
<P>
Second City Games:
</P>
<P>
Co-hosted by Tangshan and Shijiazhuang, Hebei province from
September 20 to 28 in 1991 with the participation of 2,928
athletes from 96 sports delegations.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the original 12 sports, the hosts also introduced
four more to the agenda, namely diving, archery, fencing and
canoeing.
</P>
<P>
Four Asian records were beaten by a dozen athletes, while a
pair of competitors equalized the Asian marks.
</P>
<P>
Third City Games:
</P>
<P>
Nanjing of Jiangsu province was the main competition venue for
the third edition as five more cities of Changzhou, Wuxi, Suzhou,
Yangzhou and Zhenjiang also played as co-hosts from October 22 to
30.
</P>
<P>
The number of sports remained the same as the second edition
whereas the figure of participants leapt to 3,352 from 50 sports
delegations.
</P>
<P>
Four athletes beat six world junior records 10 times, and five
Asian junior marks were outdated 10 times by eight participants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Celebrates Teachers' Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A special reception
highlighting the public's respect and appreciation to teachers was
held here Friday to mark the second Teachers' Day of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Jointly organized by the Education Department and the Committee
on Respect Our Teachers Campaign, the reception was one in a
series of activities aimed at strengthening the community's
awareness of respecting teachers.
</P>
<P>
Officiated by Chief Secretary for Administration Anson Chan,
the reception was attended by some 800 serving teachers and 200
guests including representatives from education bodies, school
councils, sponsoring bodies and retiring teachers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the reception, Chan pointed out that the aim and
direction of education should tie in with the changing needs of
the society.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from teaching knowledge, the teacher has to take on the
role to facilitate students in learning and development," she said,
expressing her hope that students appreciate their teachers on
this special day.
</P>
<P>
Earlier at the reception, a video featuring activities of the
Teachers' Day was shown. There were also performances by the Hong
Kong Principals Chorus and the Students Chorus.
</P>
<P>
Some of the guests, together with their former teachers, were
interviewed to share with other participants their student-teacher
relationship and express openly their gratitude to their teachers.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the HKSAR, in his policy
address of 1997, declared September 10 each year as the "Teachers'
Day" to serve as a reminder to all students and the community of
the importance of the teaching profession. 
</P>
