<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers Support Realization of E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ministers attending the 11th
Ministerial Meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) forum have approved measures for moving more rapidly toward
paperless trading throughout the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement adopted at the end of the two-day ministerial
meeting Friday said the ministers accorded high priority to a
number of targets for achieving paperless trading, where possible,
by 2005 for developed APEC member economies and 2010 for
developing ones.
</P>
<P>
"Electronic commerce has the potential to provide an
extraordinary stimulus to regional growth and trade," the
statement said. It added that the private sector has the key role
in driving change and innovation and the primary role of the
public sector is to ensure a favorable regulatory environment for
electronic commerce to flourish.
</P>
<P>
APEC member economies should pay particular attention to the
needs of consumers and small businesses, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the participating ministers encouraged APEC
member economies to take advantage of the self-assessment tool for
electronic commerce readiness to be developed by officials and the
private sector and tasked officials to further refine the
assessment tool and report back next year.
</P>
<P>
They directed officials to develop effective data and
indicators of electronic commerce uptake in APEC member economies
and encouraged APEC member economies to consider the model law of
the U.N. Commission for International Trade Law in developing
their regulatory frameworks.
</P>
<P>
They also instructed officials to initiate work on consumer
protection, focusing on information sharing, benchmarking and best
practices and to develop an APEC-wide plan to support the use of
electronic commerce by small- and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to the joint statement, the participating ministers
welcomed proposals from Japan to host an APEC electronic commerce
convention and an electronic commerce leaders seminar and by
Brunei and Japan to co-host a workshop on electronic commerce in
June next year.
</P>
<P>
The two-day ministerial meeting was in preparation for the 7th
informal meeting of APEC leaders scheduled for September 12 and 13
in Auckland, the largest city of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
APEC was established in 1989 in response to the growing
interdependence among Asia-Pacific economies. It is a grouping of
21 regional economies set up to improve the stability, security
and prosperity of its peoples.
</P>
<P>
It now groups Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, China's
Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua
New Guinea, Peru, the Philippines, Russia, Singapore, South Korea,
Chinese Taipei, Thailand, the United States and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
