<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ITF Suggests Two Priorities for Chinese Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- It is a real problem that
China, such a densely populated country, is yet to put itself on
the map of world tennis.
</P>
<P>
International Tennis Federation(ITF) has made the prescription
for the development of Chinese tennis and suggested two main
priorities including coaches training and junior development.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Frank Couraud, the ITF development project
administrator, laid his fingers on the weakness of the Chinese
coaches, saying that they have fell short of tennis theories.
</P>
<P>
"They have to receive tennis education which did not exist here
before. They did study something about the sports science but not
specific to tennis," said the official who came here to help
organise a clinic for coaches from across the country.
</P>
<P>
Frank, who has learned Chinese at the Paris University, added
in Chinese that "China has no tennis lessons."
</P>
<P>
The ITF has decided to make the Chinese coaches more conscious
of tennis as they set off giving Level One discourse in four
different cities of China this year and deliver Level Two
discourse next year.
</P>
<P>
After giving lessons at the first clinic based in Tianjin,
north of China, and produced a group of qualified tutors, Frank
shifted his teaching role to supervision here as he stood beside
the tutors, inserting his ideas from time to time to make sure his
teachings get across to the coaches.
</P>
<P>
Frank also laid bare other shortcomings of the local coaches,
saying that they need to do more to increase their "exposure" and
"knowledge".
</P>
<P>
"They need more exposure, they need to travel a lot, go outside
with the team to attend international competitions.
</P>
<P>
"And my general impression is that not everyone like to learn
knowledge," he said. "To be a good coach, you need to have
knowledge, good playing skill as well as experience outside."
</P>
<P>
Frank listed the junior development as the other priority for
Chinese tennis.
</P>
<P>
Under the sponsorship of the world tennis ruling body, China
has staged two under-14 junior tournaments in Tianjin early this
year and following that the ITF selected the best eight from the
competitors to send them to Europe this July.
</P>
<P>
"We selected four boys and four girls who are the best of them
for the European serial competitions. They spent five weeks there
and it ran quite well with one girl winning one of the four legs."
said Frank.
</P>
<P>
As for the Chinese players Frank said that they are excellent
in groundstrokes but their volley and net game remain to be
improved.
</P>
<P>
"They are strong baseliners, they have no problems in physique
at all, but their coaches need to focus not only on just how to
play forehand and backhand, they need to know how to teach net
game and have a vision of modern game that is big serve and net
game."
</P>
<P>
Asked if China will produce star players just like Peter
Sampras and Steffi Graf, Frank said that "you have to believe in
yourself, believe your potential". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
