<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Symposium on Ibis Protection Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A five-day international
symposium on the protection of the crested ibis closed today in
Yangxian County, in northwest China's Shaanxi Province, with
adoption of a draft declaration to protect the rare species.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 ibis experts and government officials from Japan,
the U.S., China and the International Nature Protection Union
attended the symposium.
</P>
<P>
The origin of the endangered species has been traced back 60
million years, with large flocks formerly existing in most part of
China, Japan and Germany. Today, the species is found only in
China.
</P>
<P>
The crested ibis population has grown from merely seven in 1981,
when it was first found in China, to the present 200-plus as a
result of environmental protection measures adopted by the Chinese
government, including a ban on fertilizer and lumbering in areas
close to the species' natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
Participants agreed that this rare species has not escaped
threat of extinction, though the number of ibis in the wild or
raised by men has increased.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
