<HEADLINE> Nigerian Faction Strife Kills Eight in Lagos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Inter-union violence among
Nigerian dock workers in in the busy Apapa wharf and Tin Can
Island in Nigeria's commercial hub Lagos has killed eight people
on Thursday and severely disrupted business activities there.
</P>
<P>
Men wielding dangerous implements seized control of the ports
Thursday before anti-riot Police Mobile Force squadrons of the
Lagos Police Command raided the offices of the Nigeria Ports
Authority and other agencies to flush out the protesters.
</P>
<P>
Lagos State Police Commissioner, Michael Okiro, confirmed the
casualties, saying that scores of people including policemen were
wounded in the clash.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper Friday quoted the commissioner as saying
that the trouble started when former executives of the dock
workers union, who were recently voted out of office, refused to
hand over to their successors.
</P>
<P>
Instead, they hired members of the union from nearby Ajegunle
to seize offices at the ports and unleash Mayhem, Okiro said.
</P>
<P>
The two sea ports are calm again and workers there are going
about their usual business, said the Lagos police chief.
</P>
<P>
About 10 persons were arrested as policemen fought the
rampaging protesters away from the sea ports and pushed them back
into the densely populated suburb of Ajegunle.
</P>
<P>
The police and the protesters exchanged gun shots until
Thursday noon. The police cordoned off the routes leading to the
riot scene and this led to chaotic traffic situation on major
highways adjoining Apapa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
