<HEADLINE> HKSAR Makes Debut in Chinese City Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, China, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) is making its debut in the fourth
Chinese City Games to be officially started here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Timothy Fok, Chef de
Mission of the HKSAR said that "we're very glad to make our first
participation in the City Games as it will serve as a great
opportunity to promote the friendships between all the
participating members."
</P>
<P>
"Being a city of ancient civilization, Xi'an has impressed me a
lot with great changes, and I'm sure the City Games will further
help develop its infrastructure." said Timothy Fok.
</P>
<P>
After China resumed its exercise of sovereignty over the HKSAR
in July, 1997, HKSAR is dispatching a 102-member delegation,
including 68 athletes, to compete in 10 sports in the quadrennial
City Games which was inaugurated in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong athletes are to compete in the sports of
badminton, canoeing, fencing, gymnastics, judo, shooting, soccer,
swimming, table tennis and track and field.
</P>
<P>
As its soccer players outplayed Chengdu 3-1 in its opener,
HKSAR is also pinning its medal hopes in the men's 60-meter sprint
in the track, and the women's 100-meter backstroke in the pool.
</P>
<P>
Besides, HKSAR also boasts of a string of players with great
potentials in the badminton, table tennis and canoeing.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, HKSAR also made its debut in the eighth Chinese
National Games held in Shanghai. 
</P>
