<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reform Income Taxation for Domestic, Foreign-Funded Ventures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- China has been studying a plan
to incorporate income tax into domestic and overseas-financed
ventures.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhiyong, head of international department of the State
Taxation Administration, said the plan incorporates two principles:
gradually granting national treatment to overseas investors; and
highlighting China's interest in industrial development by
offering preferential policies for taxation.
</P>
<P>
In an address to a recent symposium at the ongoing 3rd China
Investment and Trade Fair held in Xiamen City, Fujian Province,
Zhang explained that national treatment to overseas investors in
China requires that the foreign-financed ventures share the same
tax burdens as businesses funded solely by Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Also, overseas investors will be allowed to enter more areas
including finance, insurance, prospecting and development of
mineral resources. he said.
</P>
<P>
The plan should be conducive to diverting overseas investment
into projects capable of improving China's industrialization
standard, and into sectors of agriculture, energy, transport,
major raw materials, Zhang stressed.
</P>
<P>
He added that it would take time to finish the plan, so the
present preferential treatment in income taxation now enjoyed by
overseas-backed businesses will not be changed in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The current standards of income taxes for overseas-backed
businesses were drafted in the early years of China's opening-up
drive, including a range of favorable articles to attract overseas
investment.
</P>
<P>
The preferential sway has proved effective in attracting
overseas investors, but has created a policy gap between domestic
businesses and overseas-invested ventures. It has also led to less
diversion of overseas funds to remote and poverty-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year, taxes from foreigners, which mainly came from
overseas-financed businesses, made up 14.4 percent of China's
total industrial and commercial taxes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
