<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers Support Launch of New WTO Round Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Trade ministers
attending the 11th Ministerial Meeting of the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum Friday took a significant step
toward the launch of a new round of multilateral trade
negotiations at the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement adopted at the end of the two-day
ministerial meeting preceding the 7th informal meeting of APEC
leaders, the trade ministers participating in the meeting formally
expressed their support for the launch of a new round of WTO
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
They also encouraged the acceleration of accession negotiations
for APEC's non-WTO members in accordance with WTO rules, based on
commercially viable market access commitments and a balance of
rights and obligations. They agreed that these economies should be
able to participate in some capacity in the forthcoming WTO round.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement said the participating ministers
"reaffirmed their commitment to open regionalism and to the
multilateral trading system, underlining the critical importance
of the forthcoming WTO negotiations in liberalizing trade and
investment within the region and in encouraging growth in the
global economy."
</P>
<P>
"They agreed in addition that the agenda for the negotiations
be balanced and sufficiently broad-based to respond to the
interests of all economies, and confirmed the negotiations should
conclude within three years," it said.
</P>
<P>
The participating ministers also agreed that support for and
consultation among APEC economies about ongoing WTO negotiations
should remain a key area of APEC's work throughout the course of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The two-day ministerial meeting was in preparation for the 7th
informal meeting of APEC leaders scheduled for September 12-13 in
Auckland, the largest city of New Zealand. APEC was established in
1989 in response to the growing interdependence among Asia-Pacific
economies. It is a grouping of 21 regional economies set up to
improve the stability, security and prosperity of its peoples.
</P>
<P>
It now groups Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, China's
Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua
New Guinea, Peru, the Philippines, Russia, Singapore, South Korea,
Chinese Taipei, Thailand, the United States and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
