<HEADLINE> Lufthansa Increases Flights to China to 22 Weekly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- As of this month, Lufthansa
Airlines is to increase its weekly flights to China to 22,
according to Stefan Pichler, executive vice president sales.
</P>
<P>
Ten of the flights are to Hong Kong, seven to Beijing, and five
to Shanghai, with the number to Shanghai going up to six in 2000,
he said.
</P>
<P>
As one the world largest airlines, Lufthansa now is offering
the most flights to Asia among European carriers, with 84 per week,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 1999, the company's international flight
seat rate rose by 8.8 percent, with that in Asia up 12.3 percent,
said Pichler, adding that Lufthansa also held seven percent of the
aviation market linking Europe and China.
</P>
<P>
Pichler said that the airlines has maintained a good
relationship with China's civil aviation sector. After the opening
of new terminals at Beijing Capital Airport and the Pudong Airport
in Shanghai, Lufthansa will further improve its cooperation with
China's airlines.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Internet booking service now available in
China, Lufthansa will also employ Chinese interpreters on board,
and provide menus and movies in Chinese.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Records Export Surge in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan recorded a
long-awaited export buoyancy with a surge of 6.4 percent against a
slight increase in imports by 0.4 percent in August, slicing down
the trade deficit by 17.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the official statistics available Friday, exports
settled at 633 million U.S. dollars in August as compared to the
exports of 595 million dollars in July, projecting an improvement
of 38 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
While imports amounted to 800 million dollars in August against
those of 797 million dollars in the preceding month, slashing
trade imbalance from 202 million dollars to 167 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's exports and imports were worth 624 million dollars
and 711 million dollars in August 1998, bringing in a deficit of
85 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
