<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Killed, 5 Injured in Accident in Southern Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Seven more people have been
killed and five others injured in the latest of an unprecedented
surge of road accidents.
</P>
<P>
The accident took place Thursday on a road near the tourist
resort of Luxor, 550 kilometers south of Cairo, when a truck
crashed into a mini-bus, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
security sources said the truck ran into the bus when its
driver, identified as Sami Latif Ayyad, 30, was trying to overtake
a tractor.
</P>
<P>
The report neither mentioned the fate of the truck driver nor
gave the number of passengers on the bus.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents are common in Egypt due to high speed and
drivers' failure to abide by rules and regulations. Official
estimation has put the annual death toll at nearly 6,000, with
30,000 more injuries.
</P>
<P>
A government committee is looking into the rising number of
traffic accidents on Egyptian roads, especially in rural areas,
which the local media have dubbed "roads of death." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
