<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers on Friday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Since the legalization of donation of human sperm in 1973,
about 35,000 children have been born in France with donated sperm
and 6,000 of them have grown up. Jean-Loup Clement, a psychologist
working at the Center of Study and Conservation of Human Eggs and
Sperm based in Lyon, is making an inquiry about how the children
born of biological unknown fathers are living their difference
with others.
</P>
<P>
-- In a report entitled "A New Beginning," former British
governor in Hong Kong Chris Patten proposed that the Royal Ulster
Constabulary (RUC), the Northern Ireland police force, be reformed
to represent all the inhabitants of the British province. Invited
by British Prime Minister Tony Blair to propose the reform of the
RUC, Patten aims to depoliticize the 13,000-strong police force,
92 percent of which are made up with Protestants in a territory
with 42 percent of its population Catholic.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The market has applauded the primary results of the early
half year from big enterprises. The Paris CAC 40 stock index
attained a new record high with 4,717.42 points, which is 20
percent higher than the beginning of January. The French
automobile tire group Michelin saw its stock value rise by 12.6
percent after announcing a better performance than predicted in
the early half this year.
</P>
<P>
-- The World Health Organization has criticized the disorder in
donating medical materials to refugees. It said that more than
half of the medicines collected for the victims of conflicts and
natural disasters are not adapted to international norms.
</P>
<P>
Le Monde:
</P>
<P>
-- Born from a Big Bang 15 billion years ago, the Universe
continues to expand. Recent analysis of the star light, the
supernova, shows that far from slowing down or stabilizing, this
expansion is accelerating. Two teams of astronomers reported that
the galaxies are moving further and further away from each other
in an infinite expansion, as the Universe is afraid of vacuum and
is in a hurry to fill it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
