<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The decision to impose a full closure of the West Bank and
Gaza for the Jewish holiday was carried out in coordination with
Palestinian security forces, an army source said Thursday. The
closure was imposed after security forces were informed by
Palestinian security officials of plans by terrorists to carry out
an attack inside Israel, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel will transfer 7 percent of the West Bank to the
Palestinians after Palestinian National Authority Chairman is
expected to sign the maps outlining the first redeployment of the
Sharm el Sheikh Memorandum. Prime Minister Ehud Barak's office
issued a statement Thursday night saying the maps would "become
binding" once Arafat signs them.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with Ma'ariv, Barak said he would carry out
all his campaign promises, those on the domestic front as well as
on the peace process, during his four years of office.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with this newspaper, Bank of Israel Governor
Yaacov Frenkel said Israel is walking out of a long-term recession
and would achieve lasting economic growth from now on. 
</P>
