<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to Implement Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian side expected
the Israeli government to fully and timely implement the newly
signed peace accord to move the Mideast peace process forward,
said a senior Palestinian official here Friday.
</P>
<P>
After Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's approval of the
redeployment maps delivered to him by the Israeli side, his
political advisor Nabil Abu rdeineh told reporters that Arafat
approved the maps after studying them carefully with his military
advisors.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and his advisors expressed their hope that the Israeli
side will carry out in time the troop redeployment from the West
Bank as showed by the maps.
</P>
<P>
The maps outlined the 7 percent of the West Bank land Israel
will transfer to the Palestinian civilian administration. This is
the first-stage transfer of the West Bank land under the latest
Palestinian-Israeli peace deal signed last weekend in Egyptian Red
Sea Resort Sharm el Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Israel should pull out from another 11 percent
of the West Bank in three stages, with the remaining two taking
place on November 15 and January 20.
</P>
<P>
Abu rdeineh said Israeli side will begin the transfer within 24
hours after Arafat's approval.
</P>
<P>
The first handover does not require an Israeli troops
redeployment. The land in question has no Israeli military bases
and is sparsely populated. But the other two involve troops
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
After the signing of the new peace deal after a year of
deadlock, events were unfolding rapidly, with the first batch of
200 Palestinian political prisoners released Thursday morning, a
day ahead of time. The remaining 150 will get freedom on October 8.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli side released 200 Palestinian prisoners on
Thursday and today it delivered the maps to us, this showed
Israel wants to implement the peace accord and we hope Israel to
implement the accord totally and carry out other troop
redeployment from the West Bank," Abu rdeineh added.
</P>
<P>
According to the new deal, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
and Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas will enter the long-overdue
final status talks, which will deal with the thorny issues such as
Palestinian statehood, final borders, the status of Jerusalem, the
future of the settlements and the fate of millions of Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for the a permanent peace agreement is September
20, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
