<HEADLINE> Share Prices Edge Up on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Share prices finished
slightly higher on the Singapore Stock Market Friday as weak
sentiment gave way to optimism in the wake of the announcement of
Japan's second quarter GDP growth.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) edged up 5.65 points to
end at 2,133.07 points in fairly active dealings, but off the
intraday high of 2,155.59 points.
</P>
<P>
The total volume increased to 245.09 million shares valued at
550.47 million Singapore dollars (about 326.05 million U.S.
dollars). Decliners led advancers by 154 to 132 with 163 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Mentor topped the volume list of the day with 38.41 million
units changing hands. Omni Ind was the second heavily traded stock
with a turnover of 32.45 million shares. Gen Int was the next with
25.33 million counters transacted.
</P>
<P>
SPH was the biggest gainer of the day climbing by 50 cents to
close at 29.50 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS was the biggest loser of the day shedding
70 cents to close at 20.10 Singapore dollars. SIA sank 40 cents to
finish at 16.10 Singapore dollars. GE Life retreated 30 cents to
end at 18.00 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market opened firmer spurred by the
stronger-than-expected economic performance in Japan in the second
quarter of this year. 
</P>
