<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0850 GMT, September 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema confirmed here
Thursday evening that his government plans to send extracts from a
magistrate's investigation to NATO that claim an Italian civilian
airliner was downed in a "war scenario" 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The DC-9, which was flown by the now defunct domestic airline,
Itavia, crashed into the sea leaving all 81 on board dead off the
island of Ustica, north of Sicily on the evening of June 27, 1980.
The reason for the tragedy is still unknown. (Italy-NATO-Ustica
Tragedy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said he hoped to
resume "constructive conversations" with China when he meets
Chinese President Jiang Zemin this weekend in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving here for the informal meeting of leaders from
the Asian Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) members, Clinton
told the press that he was eager to restart talks on China's bid
to join the World Trade Organization (WTO). (US-China-Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRNS, AUSTRALIA -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin arrived in
Cairns of Queensland State on Friday to continue his state visit
to Australia.
</P>
<P>
Jiang was greeted at the airport by Peter Arnison, governor of
the Queensland State, and Peter Beattie, premier of the state. A
brief traditional welcome ceremony by aboriginals was held at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
Jiang came to Cairns, the last leg of his state visit to
Australia, from Sydney. (Australia-Jiang-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- The Palestinian and Israeli officials Friday signed the
maps outlining the handover of 7 percent more of the West Bank
land to the Palestinian civilian control.
</P>
<P>
Three days ahead of schedule, Israel will withdraw its troops
as of Friday from the 400 square kilometers of the West Bank, a
step to implement the latest Palestinian-Israeli peace accord of
the Sharm el Sheikh Memorandum signed last weekend in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat approved the redeployment maps
delivered to him by the Israeli side. (Palestine-Israel-Pullout)
</P>
