<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Pardons Over 200 Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has pardoned more than 200 prisoners, the Monitor daily
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Museveni's dispensation of mercy was contained in a letter to
Commissioner General of Prisons Joseph Etima Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 90 of the pardoned prisoners are soldiers
jailed for non-capital offences. They also include the terminally
sick, the elderly, juveniles and pregnant/breast-feeding mothers.
</P>
<P>
According to the letter, all prisoners who serve life sentences
(20 years), but are left with six to 12 months to go and those
aged 60 and above would be freed.
</P>
<P>
Etima confirmed the presidential pardon and said it relieves
the prison department of some congestion, adding that the
juveniles are waiting for the justice minister's release order.
</P>
<P>
The police commander explained that the president's prerogative
of mercy is occasional and not routine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
