<HEADLINE> China to Hold Sixth Major Cities' Summit in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Beijing recently formed the
organizing committee for the four-day Major Cities' Summit Beijing
2000, which begins on September 28 next year.
</P>
<P>
Liu Qi, mayor of Beijing and the chairman of the organizing
committee, said that Beijing will invite mayors of the 31 member
cities around the world to attend the summit meeting, the sixth of
its kind, to discuss the influence of international development
towards the cities, and their development and cooperation in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
The members will focus on the challenges brought to the cities
by the economic globalization and the fast development of
information technology, and will try to determine the most
efficient means of intensifying mutual understanding and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has also launched a website page for the summit on the
Internet, with the address 
</P>
<P>
The summit was set up in 1985. The first five summits were held
at three-year intervals in Tokyo, Istanbul, Montreal, Berlin, and
Moscow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
