<HEADLINE> Ugandan Vice-President Gets More Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Vice-President
Specioza Kazibwe has been granted additional power besides those
provided by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Kazibwe, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni said
that the additional roles of the vice-president follow the April 5
re-organization of government, the New Vision paper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president's new roles include being in charge of
countrywide political and mass mobilization, foreign policy and
international relations, the report said.
</P>
<P>
She will also widely consult with ministers on the
implementation of government policies and canvass for support in
Parliament when bills are brought for debate.
</P>
<P>
One of Kazibwe's new briefcase is being in charge of Uganda's
political and mass mobilization ahead of the forthcoming
referendum on political systems slated for July 2000.
</P>
<P>
In the April 5 surprise cabinet reshuffle, Kazibwe was dropped
as agriculture minister on recommendation by a parliamentary
committee over the valley dams scam.
</P>
<P>
She was said to have been responsible for the missing of over
three billion shillings (2.5 million U.S. dollars) earmarked for
building the valley dams upcountry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
