<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Pulls out From 7 percent of West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian and Israeli
officials Friday signed the maps outlining the handover of 7
percent more of the West Bank land to the Palestinian civilian
control.
</P>
<P>
Three days ahead of schedule, Israel will transfer as of Friday
400 square kilometers of the West Bank to the Palestinians,
another step to implement the latest Palestinian-Israeli peace
accord of the Sharm el Sheikh Memorandum signed last weekend in
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Those areas will be transferred from Area C to Area B, in which
Israel has security control while the Palestinians exercise
civilian administration.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat approved the redeployment maps
delivered to him by the Israeli side after a early morning
close-door meeting between the Palestinian and Israeli
officials. The handover took effect immediately after the
signature of Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's political advisor Nabil Abu Rdeineh told reporters
after Arafat's approval that Israel will carry out redeployment
within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
Under the new agreement, Israel should transfer another 11
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians in three stages, with
the last two taking place in November 15 and January 20 next year.
</P>
<P>
The Sharm el-Sheikh accord resulting from weeks of agonizing
negotiations also provides for the release of 350 political
Palestinian prisoners and the start of final status talks on
September 13 to deal with the thorny issues such as the borders
and nature of the Palestinian entity, and the future of the Jewish
settlements and status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The final status talks should be concluded on September 13 next
year.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 200 Palestinian political prisoners got
freedom on Thursday morning, the first step to carry out the new
accord, and the remaining 150 will be freed on October 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
