<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Chinese Cities Report Deteriorating Air Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Some Chinese cities reported
deteriorating air quality this week, according to a report
released today by the China Environment Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
China's northernmost areas, affected by a subtropical high
pressure system, reported clear weather, but suffered from
pollution caused by suspended particles in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
From September 3-9, most of China received little precipitation
and reported higher temperature than that in past years. Seven
cities -- Hohhot, Yinchuan, Lanzhou, Guangzhou, Xi'an, Taiyuan,
and Chongqing -- recorded a pollution index exceeding 100.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six cities, including Beijing, Xining, Shanghai, Tianjin,
Jinan, Hangzhou, and Shenzhen enjoyed good air quality. Thirteen
cities, including Guilin, Kunming, Hefei, and Haikou, chalked up
excellent air quality.
</P>
<P>
Hohhot, Yinchuan, Taiyuan, and Lanzhou suffered from moderate
pollution from suspended particles. The major atmospheric problem
in Guangzhou, Shanghai, Hangzhou and Shenzhen was nitrogen oxide,
while in Chongqing it was sulfur dioxide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
