<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow Blast Toll Reaches 69, Rescue Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Rescuers have pulled out 69
bodies from the rubble of an apartment building ripped apart by a
powerful explosion early Thursday in southeastern Moscow, Mayor
Yuri Luzhkov said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rescue efforts are continuing as over 50 people are still
believed to be under the debris, but not a single survivor had
been spotted for over 20 hours, the Itar-Tass news agency said.
Pockets of fire in the basements, smoke and steaming have hampered
the rescuers.
</P>
<P>
The total injured number in the blast in the nine-story
building in 19 Gurianov Street was put at 252, with 22 of them
children. A total of 46 people remain hospitalized, including two
in serious condition, Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
Investigators were still trying to determine the cause of the
blast, which was said to be equal to up to 400 kilograms of TNT.
</P>
<P>
A natural-gas explosion was initially blamed, but later a bomb
was said to be more likely.
</P>
<P>
"The nature of damage and the number of casualties" suggested
an explosive device was placed inside the building, the Federal
Security Service, the main successor to the Soviet KGB, said in a
statement, adding that no one had claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov, who has a degree in chemistry, said late Thursday that
a military explosive called hexagon was the most probable cause of
the blast, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Hexagon, also called RDX, was used by most of the warring
powers in the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
All nine stories in the center section of the block-long
building collapses in the explosion that occurred shortly after
midnight, but apartments on either side were left intact.
</P>
<P>
The blast shattered windows in buildings hundreds of meters
away from the scene and turned over cars in surrounding streets.
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov said 15 buildings were damaged, mainly with windows
shattered, and a nearby school and kindergarten lost windows,
doors and doorframes. About 800 apartments would have to be
repaired, while the people registered in 286 apartments would have
to be relocated.
</P>
<P>
An anonymous caller with a Caucasus accent told Interfax on
Thursday that the apartment explosion and a Saturday night bomb
blast in Buinaksk, Daghestan, were in response to Russia's
military campaign against Islamic rebels in the southern territory
of the republic bordering the breakaway Chechnya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
