<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministerial Meeting Ends With Joint Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The 11th
Ministerial Meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) forum ended here Friday with the adoption of a joint
statement focusing on future tasks of the 21-member APEC.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement covers a wide-ranging package of
initiatives to support the development of the World Trade
Organization (WTO), strengthen markets, improve conditions for
business, assist developing members of APEC, and accelerate
actions on electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
On the development of the WTO, the joint statement said that
the ministers who participated in the meeting agreed that their
meeting was a historic opportunity for APEC to contribute to the
successful launch of a new round of WTO negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"They reaffirmed their commitment to opening regionalism and to
the multilateral trading system, underlining the critical
importance of the forthcoming WTO negotiations in liberalizing
trade and investment within the region and in encouraging growth
in the global economy," the joint statement said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers in the statement strongly emphasized the
importance of working together to strengthen markets in the region
to facilitate regional economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"Strengthening markets provides an integrative framework that
can bring together APEC's work in key areas such as trade and
investment, competition and regulatory reform and capacity
building, with a view to generating sustained growth in APEC
economies," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the participating ministers also emphasized the
importance of improving conditions for business through such
measures as trade facilitation.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the ministers called for efforts
for assisting developing members of APEC.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers agreed that the concerns of developing economies
should be addressed through enhanced attention to the effective
implementation of special and differential treatment and ongoing
support for capacity building and technical assistance, so as to
facilitate their ability to participate fully in the WTO," it
said.
</P>
<P>
On electronic commerce, the statement emphasized that
"Electronic commerce has the potential to provide an extraordinary
stimulus to regional growth and trade." The participating
ministers encouraged APEC members to adopt measures to promote the
development of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
The two-day ministerial meeting was in preparation for the 7th
informal meeting of APEC leaders scheduled for September 12-13 in
Auckland, the largest city of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The agenda of the ministerial meeting was structured to reflect
the three themes of the 7th informal meeting of APEC leaders:
expanding opportunities for business around the region,
strengthening the functioning of markets, and broadening support
for APEC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
