<HEADLINE> Both Stocks, Dollar Up in Tokyo on Dollar-Supportive Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed moderately
higher in Tokyo on Friday, helped by the U.S. dollar's upturn
against the yen following the Bank of Japan's (BOJ) dollar-
supportive market intervention.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 33.46 points, or 0.19
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 17,711.02.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 7.24 points or 0.48 percent to 1,514.
86.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index opened lower after the dollar had plunged to a
three-year low of 107.55 yen at one stage in New York on Thursday,
but turned upward soon after as the dollar rebounded following the
BOJ's market intervention.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, the key market gauge lost upward momentum,
partly because the dollar weakened slightly, dampening market
sentiment again, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section ballooned to 1,172.08 million
shares from 474.00 million shares Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers exceeded
gainers 658 to 565 despite the overall gain in the Nikkei index,
with 120 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar rose sharply
against the yen on the BOJ's market intervention.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the U.S. currency was quoted at 108.90-93 yen, up
from 107.71-74 yen at 9 a.m., and from 108.00-10 yen in New York
overnight. The dollar was traded at 108.82-85 yen in Tokyo late
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
