<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. National Semiconductor Corp. Reports Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The National Semiconductor
Corp., a leading U.S. maker of semiconductors for cell phones and
wireless devices, on Thursday reported unexpected profits in its
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Revenue rose 2.6 percent to 481.8 million U.S. dollars for the
fiscal first quarter ended August 29, from 469.6 million dollars
in the same period of last year, the company said.
</P>
<P>
The Santa Clara, California-based company had a profit of 47.1
million dollars for the quarter, compared to a loss of 104.8
million dollars a year earlier, said National Semiconductor
spokesman Bill Callahan.
</P>
<P>
"They've certainly eliminated those parts of the business that
were hemorrhaging the worst and what's left happens to be enjoying
a huge boom," said analyst Drew Peck at SG Cowen. "National Semi
is now in a much better place."
</P>
<P>
Last week, National Semiconductor completed its exit from its
Cyrix microprocessor business after an attempt to compete with
chip giant Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
The company said it was ahead of schedule in returning to
profitability and that orders during the normally slow summer
quarter were stronger than expected.
</P>
<P>
Orders for its analog chips, its core business, rose 57 percent
from a year ago, led by wireless circuits and other power-
management devices used in cell phones, among other equipment.
</P>
<P>
"The analog market is strong and the industry, overall, is
moving into the sweet spot of a (recovery) cycle," said analyst
Mark Edelstone at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
