<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Rules out Further Maize Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
ruled out further importation of maize in a bid to protect the
interest of the local maize farmers.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Agriculture Minister Chris Obure said Thursday that as
long as Kenya has the capacity to produce them, maize must not be
imported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister said that maize harvesting has started
in parts of the east African country and initial fears over maize
shortage have been allayed after a two million bags (180,000 tons)
of imports.
</P>
<P>
In late July this year, the Kenyan government lowered import
duty on maize from 32.5 percent to 25 percent after poor rains
which augured a shortfall in food.
</P>
<P>
Kenya will not allow importation of agricultural products which
Kenya can produce, the Daily Nation newspaper Friday quoted the
minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The cheap imports of eggs, onions and sugar are flooding
Kenya's domestic market, Obure noted, citing that it would hurt
the economy badly.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, agriculture accounts for about 80
percent of the country's employment and is the backbone of the
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
