<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Form Medical Services Inspection Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
planned to establish an inspection and audit unit as a measure to
ensure efficient delivery of medical services to Kenyans and to
eradicate corruption in the Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The plan was announced here Thursday by Minister for Medical
Service Amukowa Anangwe, who is one of the two ministers of the
Health Ministry appointed by President Daniel arap Moi Monday.
</P>
<P>
The unit will conduct random checks and inspections in
government health institutions to ensure that drugs and other
medical supplies reach their intended destinations, the Kenya
Times newspaper Friday quoted Anangwe as saying
</P>
<P>
"This will completely eradicate the rampant theft of drugs and
other medical supplies in government hospitals," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Anangwe vowed that "my main aim in the ministry is to put in
place adequate reform to improve the provision of health services
and make the facilities accessible to all citizens, in line with
the government policy to provide health services to all."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that he would streamline the contentious
tendering system in the ministry which has over years raised
concern with revelations of briefcase agents jamming in the
ministry building to manipulate the tendering.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his government will reduce the percentage of
inpatient and outpatient services in the government health
institutions to enable the private sector to play a big role in
the delivery of such services.
</P>
<P>
However, he emphasized that his ministry will remain in charge
of regulations of medical services in the east African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
