<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Airline Complaints Hit 11-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 9 (Xinhua) -- American consumers'
complaints against all carriers hit an 11-year high in July,
according to the latest figures released by the U.S. Department of
Transportation on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 2,485 overall complaints nearly doubled the June's record
of 1,332 and marked the highest number since March 1988, said the
department, adding that nearly half dealt with flight problems,
including delays, missed connections and canceled flights.
</P>
<P>
Consumers filed 2,111 complaints against U.S. carriers and the
rest against foreign carriers, tour operators, travel agents and
others.
</P>
<P>
American Airlines, the nation's second-largest carrier, led all
major U.S. airlines in passenger complaints, while Southwest
Airlines had the fewest complaints and the best on-time
performance, the department added.
</P>
<P>
"We're thrilled," said Melanie Jones, a spokeswoman for
Southwest. "It's gratifying to see our emphasis on service
reflected in the numbers."
</P>
<P>
American Airline spokesman Tim Smith explained that his company
was the hardest hit by Federal Aviation Administration computer
upgrades that slowed air-traffic control operations in Dallas-Fort
Worth, Chicago and Cleveland. He said the airline has taken steps,
such as more-timely boarding, to improve on-time performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
