<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Deputy PM to Attend Singapore-China Joint Steering Council Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Deputy Prime
Minister Lee Hsien Loong will lead a delegation to attend the 4th
Singapore-China Joint Steering Council Meeting on the Suzhou
Industrial Park (SIP) to be held in Suzhou, China on September 14,
Singapore's Ministry of Trade and Industry (MTI) announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
MTI said the 4th JSC Meeting is expected to review the progress
of the SIP, endorse the MOU signed in Singapore on June 28, 1999,
chart out the SIP's next phase of development and consider
proposals to further enhance the SIP's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
MTI said Lee will leave for China on September 13 and beside
co-chairing the JSC meeting, he will tour the SIP, attend the
ground- breaking of a residential project and visit some companies
in the SIP.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister will also visit Nanjing and Shanghai,
MTI added.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore and Chinese working teams on the SIP reached
agreement earlier this year on a package of solutions to put the
SIP project on a more successful footing and signed a MOU on June
28, in which both sides agreed that the China-Singapore SIP
Development Co Ltd (CSSD)'s current priority is to concentrate on
developing the first eight Square kilometers of the total area of
70 square kilometers and strive to complete it by January 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also agreed that from January 1, 2001, the Chinese
Consortium will increase its shareholding in the CSSD from 35
percent to 65 percent while the Singapore consortium will reduce
its shareholding in the CSSD from 65 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
