<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Quarter Students in United States Shun Closest School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 9 (Xinhua) -- About one in four U.S.
children are going to alternative and private schools as choices
other than neighborhood public schools are increasing, a new study
found.
</P>
<P>
The percentage attending private schools has remained at 10
percent for years, according to the study released Thursday by the
Policy Analysis for California Education (PACE).
</P>
<P>
But with newer options of charter schools, magnet schools, open
enrollment and voucher programs, the alternatives -- including
private schools -- account for a full 25 percent of U.S. students,
said PACE, which is based at the University of California,
Berkeley, and Stanford University. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Newspaper Advertising Spending Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. newspapers spent 21.6
billion U.S. dollars on advertising in the first half of 1999, up
5.1 percent from the same period last year, according to a report
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Newspaper Association of America (NAA) said that the
statistics showed retail up 3 percent to 9.7 billion dollars,
classified up 3.9 percent to 8.5 billion and national advertising
increasing 15.1 percent to 3.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
"Advertisers continue to increase their investment in
newspapers as the economy expands," John F. Sturm, the NAA
president and chief executive officer, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter of 1999, the report said, classified grew
4 percent to 4.4 billion dollars, national was up 17.4 percent to
1.8 billion and retail advertisement rose 1.8 percent to 5.1
billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
