<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Old Industrial Base Seeking to Recover Past Glory (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As for the many liabilities, backward technology, inefficient
management, redundant workers, and unreasonable product mix in the
province's state sector, Wen said that a promising future means
nothing if these problems are not tackled.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Liaoning is changing from a planned economy
to a market economy and its industry, from the traditional
industry to a technology-based one.
</P>
<P>
China said in 1997 that it would get most of its debt-ridden
state-owned enterprises out of difficulties in three years, and
Liaoning is being given priority in this.
</P>
<P>
It's impossible to solve all the problems of the past in the
short term, Wen said. It will take time and be a painful process.
But, to shorten that process, Liaoning is focusing on three major
campaigns at present: transforming state-owned enterprises into
stock companies that are modern enterprises, freeing state-owned
enterprises from the heavy employee burden, and streamlining the
workforce and improving efficiency.
</P>
<P>
There is no shortcut in this, Wen emphasized. Even in the West,
it takes 15 to 20 years to complete the task, how much more so in
Liaoning, whose industry is a relic of the planned economy.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has had some results in its enterprise reforms, said
Wen, who expressed confidence in giving Liaoning a new image and
taking a developed, prosperous, and civilized Liaoning into the
next century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
