<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Old Industrial Base Seeking to Recover Past Glory (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning, a former center of
China's heavy industry in the northeast, is making an effort to
recover its past glory and rebuild its economy.
</P>
<P>
"Liaoning's glorious chapter is already some in the past and we
are restructuring the state sector to put the province in the
market economy," provincial governor Wen Shizhen told Xinhua
recently.
</P>
<P>
Wen, a former engineer and leading official in charge of the
industrial sector, is a witness to Liaoning's industrialization
over the past 50 years. He said the province's industry was built
upon the rubble of the war after the New China was established and
its key enterprises became the backbone of the nation's industry.
</P>
<P>
By the early 1980s, Liaoning was the country's first in terms
of fixed assets and heavy industrial output and was a leading
producer of steel, cement, machine tool, mining equipment and
other major machinery products. It contributed a lot to New China'
s industrialization and formation of the national economic
structure, Wen said.
</P>
<P>
By providing various products to other parts of the country and
providing thousands of technicians and managers for the industrial
sector, the province was extremely importance to the entire nation
at that time, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning then became a forerunner in the reform and opening-up
drive that started two decades ago and shared much of the burden
of those economic reforms. It has contributed about 200 billion
yuan to state coffers since 1980, several times the state's
spending on the province.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, one shouldn't keep talking about the glorious
past because there is still a promising future that needs an all-
out effort by all of the province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
