<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan's Yangpu Ready for Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Yangpu Economic Development
Zone in south China's Hainan Province is now ready to receive
overseas investment, Deputy Governor Li Dongsheng said Thursday
during a press conference on investment environment and policies
of the state-level zone.
</P>
<P>
Set up with the approval of the State Council, Yangpu Economic
Development Zone has an area of 31 sq km. A total of 5.3 billion
yuan was spent to build infrastructure systems, including
transportation, power supply to telecommunications facilities.
</P>
<P>
The zone is now home to a power plant with a generating
capacity of 315,500 kw, one 10,000-dwt (dead weight tonnages) fuel
dock and three berths each with an annual handling capacity of one
million tons, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
Construction is underway on a 35,000-dwt multi-purpose berth,
two 35,000-dwt universal berths, a new road project connecting the
nearby highway, as well as a water diversion project.
</P>
<P>
Li said the zone will be turned into an export-oriented
industrial area dominated by technologically advanced industries,
supplemented by the service trade.
</P>
<P>
Ma Xiuhong, assistant minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation, said that Yangpu is the only a development zone where
bonded policies are applied extensively. She believed that it is a
suitable site for starting up new industrial projects and
developing export processing trade.
</P>
<P>
China now has 32 state-level economic development zones where
preferential policies are offered. By the end of 1998, a total of
25.22 billion U.S. dollars of overseas investment was put into the
development zones, accounting for about 10 percent of the country'
s total. These zones also exported 11.3 billion U.S. dollars worth
of commodities, making up 6.15 percent of the country's total
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
