<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Serf Now Living Happier Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Although he's shy and not very
talkative, Nyima Cering can become very animated when he recalls
how 300 serfs and slaves belonging to Surkang escaped his rule
during the democratic reforms in Tibet in 1959.
</P>
<P>
The democratic reforms helped slaves and serfs become masters,
Nyima Cering says. His village, Kesong, was the first in the Tibet
Autonomous Region to set up a People's Congress and they now elect
their leaders directly, he says proudly.
</P>
<P>
Under the feudal serf system that existed in Tibet for
centuries, slaves and serfs were treated like talking animals, he
says, and didn't have enough to eat or any kind of personal
freedom.
</P>
<P>
The owners could punish them in any way or torture or kill them,
he says, and can still recall Surkang's words about them being his
property and how he could treat them any way he liked.
</P>
<P>
Nyima Cering was a serf since the age of 8. The annual harvest
at Surkang's large manor produced 210,000 kg. of grain, 168,000 kg.
of that going to Surkang and the rest to the more than 300 serfs.
Some serfs had to go out and beg for food.
</P>
<P>
The village of 1,000 people now has more than 100 threshing,
sowing, and reaping machines and has had good harvests for 11
consecutive years. In 1998, total grain output was 835,000 kg., a
per ha. output of 8,250 kg., 10.7 times the amount in 1959. The
average annual per capita incomes was 1,587 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Nyima Cering built a 200-sq.m. house several years ago and is
now quite satisfied with his life. The serf owner's manor in the
past was just so-so when compared with his new house, he says
proudly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
