<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 5,500 Africans Die of AIDS Daily: UNAIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Over 5,500 people die of AIDS
in Africa everyday, the United Nations AIDS (UNAIDS) has said.
</P>
<P>
According to a UNAIDS report available here Friday, AIDS was
responsible for an estimated two million African deaths in the
course of 1998, or 5,500 deaths a day.
</P>
<P>
"The sheer number of Africans affected by the epidemic is
overwhelming. Since HIV began spreading, an estimated 34 million
people living in sub- Saharan Africa have been infected with the
virus. Some 11.5 million of those people have already died, a
quarter of them children," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS report points out that despite the scale of death
there were more Africans living with HIV than ever before --
21.5million adults and a further one million children.
</P>
<P>
"While no country in Africa has escaped the virus, some are far
more severely affected than others. The bulk of new infections
continue to be concentrated in east and especially in southern
Africa," the report states.
</P>
<P>
It also indicates that the southern part of the African
continent holds the majority of the hard hit countries.
</P>
<P>
In Botswana, Namibia, Swaziland and Zimbabwe, current estimates
show that between 20 and 26 percent of the people aged between 15
and 49 are living with HIV or AIDS.
</P>
<P>
It also states that the sub-Saharan Africa was home to 70
percent of the people who became infected with HIV last year and
four-fifths of all AIDS deaths which occurred in 1998 were from
the region.
</P>
<P>
Among children under 15, Africa's share of new 1998 infections
was nine out of ten and at least 95 percent of all AIDS orphans
were African. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
