<HEADLINE> Liquid Found in 2,000-Year-Old Wine Pots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts said here today
that they have found liquid in one of the two bronze wine pots
dating back to the Warring States period (475-221 B.C.) that were
recently unearthed in Yijun County of Shaanxi Province, northwest
China.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory tests on the liquid have not yet begun, but
archeologists have shown keen interest in the 2,000-year-old stuff.
</P>
<P>
The drinking pot with liquid stands about 20 centimeters high,
and the other, a dozen centimeters. There are no inscriptions on
the vessels, which were used by nobles of that period,
archeologists noted.
</P>
<P>
The pots were found in a cellar by workers during construction
of a highway.  
</P>
