<HEADLINE> Classified Management on Processing Trade Remains Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- China's plan to change its
controls on the processing business by introducing a different
form of management October 1 remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Gao Hucheng, the assistant minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, told a press conference here Thursday that
the new management system is designed to make operations fairer.
He explains that the present management methods have proven too
costly and difficult and leave room for loopholes and illegal
activities like smuggling, fraud, and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Gao says that China will continue its policies that encourage
the processing trade and will not change certain principles. The
performance of processing companies will be the main basis for
classification, which will be dynamic.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's highest governing body, earlier
decided to change the day of implementing the management scheme
from July 1 to October 1. 
</P>
