<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 06:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Assess Industrial Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon is going to conduct
the first industrial survey since 1994 to assess the strength of
local industries.
</P>
<P>
Industry Minister Nasser Saidi said the survey would cover
3,000 major industrial plants.
</P>
<P>
The survey, whose date has not been fixed yet, will involve
detailed forms to be filled out by industrialists as well as
interviews and workshops, the Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 20-page form will include information on the number of the
company's workers, its products, capital, financial statements,
location and size of factories, salary scales and plans for future
investment.
</P>
<P>
The results will later be used in discussions on the viability
of trade agreements and appropriate levels for Customs duties.
</P>
<P>
It will help the government assess the prospect of industrial
investment and find new channels to help industrialists market
their goods.
</P>
<P>
Saidi urged local industrialists to provide accurate
information about their businesses, adding that "accurate
information will lead to realistic solutions."
</P>
<P>
"The survey will help us draft a new policy for industry and
identify companies that have the ability to compete," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has 22,107 large, medium and small industrial
enterprises that employ 145,000 workers, according to a
unofficial survey in 1996. Nearly 70 percent of those companies
hire less than five people each. 
</P>
