<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, Sri Lanka Sign Flight Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Nepal and Sri Lanka have
agreed to allow the specific airlines of both countries to operate
four flights a week to each country, The Rising Nepal reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
An agreement to this effect was signed here by the civil
aviation ministries of the two countries Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As against the previous arrangement under which the specific
Nepalese airlines was allowed to make Male, capital of the
Maldives, an intermediate or beyond point and carry not more than
60 passengers from Colombo, the new agreement will allow the
Nepalese airlines to use Male as an intermediate or beyond point
by exercising the fifth freedom traffic right and carry all
passengers.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, as against the previous arrangement under which the
specific airlines of Sri Lanka was allowed to make Bangladesh an
intermediate or beyond point and carry not more than 60 passengers
from Bangladesh, the new agreement will allow the specific Sri
Lankan airlines to use Bangladesh as an intermediate or beyond
point by exercising the fifth freedom traffic right and carry all
passengers.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have also agreed to exchange drafts for
updating the existing air service agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
