</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Better Life for Ethnic Group Living in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- China's rapid development has
brought about tremendous changes to the daily life of members of
the Monba ethnic group in the Tibetan Autonomous Region, southwest
China.
</P>
<P>
The Monba ethnic group, with a population of about 7,400, is
one of the 56 ethnic groups in China. The Monbas have their own
spoken language, but no written form. Their close contacts with
Tibetans over the centuries have helped most of them learn Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
They live in an area with adequate rainfall, fertile soil, and
rich produce, but these advantages didn't help them much until
1959, the year of the Democratic Reform in Tibet. Today, their
ancient methods of keeping records by carving signs on wood and
making calculations with knots on a rope are becoming distant
memories.
</P>
<P>
One eyewitness to the history is Ngawang Yuzhen who is about 87
although he is not certain because there are no accurate records.
Ngawang Yuzhen lives an easy life in Cona County like many other
elderly people, watching TV and drinking buttered tea and barley
wine.
</P>
<P>
Ngawang Yuzhen says that the new life of the Monbas started
with the Democratic Reform and in 1964 they were recognized by the
State Council as an ethnic minority. They say that recalling their
terrible life before 1959 is unbearable because most of them were
forced to live in remote, mountainous areas by the local Tibetan
government, the monasteries, and the nobility.
</P>
<P>
At that time, they lived a "barbaric" life and had no choice
but to live in thatched-roof cottage, eating wild herbs, and
drinking a substance made from the bark of trees. Most of them
went around barefoot and did hard labor for the landlords.
</P>
<P>
After 1959, the central and local government have spent large
sums of money on primary and middle schools in Monba areas and
some of them have trucks and have opened shops or put up new
buildings.
</P>
<P>
The Monbas now study Tibetan and Chinese and an increasing
number of them receive a higher education and have found jobs in
big cities. Some have even been selected as deputies to the
National People's Congress, the country's highest legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pioline Advances to Semifinals at U.S. Open (Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Veteran Cedric Pioline of
France continued his astounding success in tiebreakers this year,
defeating fifth seed Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil to earn a berth in
the semifinals of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
Piloine improved to 26-9 in tiebreakers this season and
advanced to his fourth career Grand Slam semifinal with a 4-6, 7-6
(8-6), 7-6 (16-14), 7-6 (10-8) win over Kuerton.
</P>
<P>
Piloine, a runner-up here in 1993, will take on the winner of
tonight's match between No. 7 Todd Martin of the United States and
unseeded Czech Slava Dosedel on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm trying to be aggressive in the tiebreak," said Pioline,
who is unbeaten in three meetings with Kuerten. "If you stay back,
you're going to give opportunities to your opponent. Since the
beginning of the year, I have a good tiebreak record so I feel
very good when it's coming."
</P>
<P>
Pioline, whose five matches have averaged around three hours,
is into his first Grand Slam semifinal since the 1998 French Open.
He had lost in the first round of four of his previous five Grand
Slam tournaments before this week.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten, the 1997 French Open champion, was looking to become
the first Brazilian in the Open era to reach the semifinals of the
U.S. Open. He hit 19 aces and won 87 percent of his first-service
points but took advantage of just 2-of-8 break-point chances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
