<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Aims to Lure More Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will seek to lure
more airlines into the country to make it a hub of international
air traffic under a five-year development program, officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
They said under the program for the period of 1999 to 2004, the
government is seeking to attract foreign carriers from countries
such as Australia, Austria, China, Italy and Japan, which have air
service agreements with Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
At present only 21 airlines operate to Sri Lanka although 53
countries have reached bilateral air service agreements and have
right of access, said a document released by the Tourism and Civil
Aviation Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Most airlines had stopped operating to Colombo due to
inadequate load factors.
</P>
<P>
The country's own airline, now known as Sri Lankan Airlines,
had sustained and nurtured the tourist inflow when many scheduled
and nonscheduled carriers withdrew from Sri Lanka, said the
document.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Airlines carries more than 50 percent of the tourist
traffic to the country.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Sri Lanka will benefit from a great
increase of volume of air traffic in the Asia and Pacific region,
said the document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
