<HEADLINE> Clinton Hopes to Resume "Constructive" Talks With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said he hoped to resume "constructive conversations" with China
when he meets Chinese President Jiang Zemin this weekend in New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving here for the informal meeting of leaders from
the Asian Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) countries, Clinton
told the press that he was eager to restart talks on China's bid
to join the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
"We have done our best to do what I think is the honorable and
decent thing in the wake of the terrible accident involving the
embassy in Belgrade," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has have made it clear in recent
tensions across the Taiwan Straits "we still support the 'one
China 'policy," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade in May
seriously hurt relations between China and the United States and
brought WTO negotiations to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he hoped to "resume constructive conversations
with the Chinese, beginning with my meeting with President Jiang
and I would very much like to resume the WTO negotiations."
</P>
<P>
"I think it would be good for China, good for the United
States and good for the world economic system," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
