<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Peace Talks to Complete in One Year: Shaath </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Talks of the Middle East
peace process will end in one year, as the newly adopted deal has
expected, a Palestinian minister said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Shaath, Palestinian Minister of Planning and
International Cooperation, who negotiated the September 3
agreement with Israel following the Wye River peace accord, said
that one year is sufficient to end the talks if both sides come
with good intention and good planning.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after his one-day visit to Finland, present
holder of the rotating Presidency of European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
During his visit, he said, he informed Tarja Halonen, Finnish
foreign minister, of the general situation of the Middle East
peace process and details of the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also discussed economic relations between EU
and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
The new agreement on revisions to the Wye River land-for-
security accord gives Palestine and Israel one year to strike a
final peace, settling contentious issues of Palestinian statehood
and border, the future of Jerusalem and Jewish settlements, water
and the fate of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Palestine eagerly wishes the presence of the EU in the peace
process, especially in the negotiations, said Shaath.
</P>
<P>
A prompt and word-to-word implementation of the new agreement
is very important, he added, for it will enhance the Palestinians'
support to the agreement and the confidence between Yasser Arafat
and Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
On her part, Tarja Halonen agreed that a strict implementation
of the agreement is important, stressing that the EU will keep
supporting the programs it has promised to attend.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish FM told the press that David Levy, the Israel
foreign minister, has already been invited to visit her country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
