<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Private Economy Developing Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The private sector has become
an important part of China's economy, according to the deputy
secretary-general of the China Association of Individual Laborers.
</P>
<P>
The private economy has been growing fast since China began
opening to the outside world in 1978 and, by late 1998, there were
1.2 million private enterprises employing 17 million people. They
had 1.02 trillion yuan in registered capital, 585.3 billion yuan
in output value, and did 532.3 billion yuan worth of business.
</P>
<P>
There were also 31.2 million small businesses by 1998 with 312
billion yuan in registered capital and 61.1 million employees.
They had 596 billion yuan worth of output value and 1.75 trillion
yuan worth of business.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, private enterprises and companies had earnings of 18.
76 billion yuan from exports while small businesses earned 2.27
billion yuan from exports.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, private enterprises paid well over 70 billion
yuan in taxes, or 8.5 percent of total industrial and commercial
taxes in China.
</P>
<P>
The development of the private economy has provided jobs for
workers in urban areas, unemployed people, and surplus labor from
rural areas. In the past year the private sector provided 3.1
million new jobs for people who had been laid off.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
