<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Urges NATO to Investigate Ustica Air Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'
Alema confirmed here Thursday evening that his government plans to
send extracts from a magistrate's investigation to NATO that claim
an Italian civilian airliner was downed in a "war scenario" 19
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The DC-9, which was flown by the now defunct domestic airline,
Itavia, crashed into the sea leaving all 81 on board dead off the
island of Ustica, north of Sicily on the evening of June 27, 1980.
The reason for the tragedy is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is for NATO and our allies to help us throw
light on the tragedy," said D'Alema at a joint press conference
with NATO's outgoing Secretary-General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
The decision to send NATO and individual allies, especially the
United States and France, extracts from the 5,400-page indictment
and report, which was drawn up by the Roman investigating
magistrate Rosario Priore, was discussed when Priore submitted the
results of his nine-year investigation last week.
</P>
<P>
Solana, on a visit to Rome before becoming the European Union's
spokesman for foreign and security affairs, said NATO will
continue to provide cooperation on clarifying responsibilities in
the disaster.
</P>
<P>
"As NATO's secretary-general, it has been my responsibility to
work for the greatest possible disclosure," he told the press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The report of Priore indicated that the DC-9 airplane may have
been hit by crossfire in a battle between four American and two
French warplanes, and Libyan MiG fighters. But the U.S. and France
have denied any involvement in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, Libyan leader Mouammer al Gaddafi has claimed
the DC-9 was downed in an attack aimed at assassinating him as he
flew across the Mediterranean to visit Poland.
</P>
<P>
Priore's report says one or perhaps more Libyan planes may have
been involved in the "war scenario."
</P>
<P>
Claiming himself as a witness to the disaster, Gaddafi said
that from his plane, he saw the U.S. Navy exercises near Ustica.
The U.S. Navy tried to hit his plane, but hit the DC-9 instead,
the Libyan leader claimed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
