<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consensus Reached on World Anti-doping Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, Switzerland, September 9 (Xinhua) - The International
Olympic Committee (IOC) said on Thursday a working group had
reached a consensus on Thursday that on a possible structure for
the World Anti-doping Agency, which was called for by the World
Conference on Doping in Sport.
</P>
<P>
The working group, which includes the associations of winter
and summer sports federations, the European Union, the IOC
athletes commission, the World Health Organization and the IOC,
reached agreement on the structure of the new agency which it
hopes will begin work in the new year.
</P>
<P>
Documents will be finalized and submitted to political and
sports authorities for approval.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the IOC said the agency's principal task would
be to coordinate a comprehensive anti-doping program at
international level, developing common, effective minimum
standards for doping control, particularly out of competition
testing.
</P>
<P>
The agency is also expected to work with existing authorities
to promote the harmonization of anti-doping policies and
procedures, identify a reference laboratory to advise testing
laboratories and publish an annual list of prohibited substances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
