<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's "Twice-Born Paddies" Fading Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ratooning paddy growing
methods that were once encouraged by the government are gradually
fading away as China manages to produce sufficient food for its
more than 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese have developed farming methods on ratooning paddies
for over 1,700 years, agronomists say. After farmers harvested the
grain, they would leave the straw in the field and fertilize it,
and from it there would grow a second crop in 70 days, thus it was
widely known as "twice-born paddy".
</P>
<P>
But, the centuries-old method did not really take off until the
late 1980s, when China suffered successive setbacks in grain
output for many years. From 1990 to 1995, the "twice-born paddy"
method was used on more than two million hectares of farmland to
produce 6.2 billion kg of grain.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, however, steady grain production has left surpluses
in grain storehouses across the country as a result of the
government's agricultural policies and a number of new farming
technologies, and the Chinese no longer worry about food supplies.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that grain output has increased to the
present 500 billion kg from 113 billion kg in 1949, when the
People's Republic of China was founded.
</P>
<P>
Last year, grain production entered a new era as the government
announced that more importance would be placed on quality instead
of quantity in order to meet the demand of consumers for better
products. "Twice-born paddy", which once contributed greatly to
the people's bowls, has become increasingly something in the past
due to its poor quality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0290 </DOCNO>
