<DOCNO> XIE19990910.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economy Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Germany's gross domestic
product (GDP) grew by a mere 0.8 percent in the first six months
of this year in real terms, slower than the 1.9 percent GDP growth
rate for the same period last year, Germany's statistics office
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The economy effectively stagnated in the second quarter of this
year as a result of shrinking exports, the office said. But it
added that growing internal demand, particularly increasing
investment in equipment and private consumption, helped the
economy avoid negative growth.
</P>
<P>
The German Finance Ministry attributed the economic slowdown to
slumping exports due to a worldwide economic depression. The
government estimated that due to weak exports, the economic growth
rate for 1999 will be lower than last year, when the country
registered a 2.2 percent GDP growth rate, the highest since its
reunification years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the economic circle and the government have expressed
optimism about the overall economic situation next year. German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder predicted a 2.5 percent economic
growth rate for 2000, while the Bundesbank forecast a 3 percent
rate.
</P>
<P>
These optimists explained that Germany's exports would boom
again in 2000 when the global economy is expected to turn for the
better, with the Asian economies starting to recover and the U.S.
economy sustaining growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many major German banks said that increasing
domestic demand will continue to stimulate the economic growth
next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
