<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks: World Cup Bid "Still on Course" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The former sports minister, now in charge of the World Cup bid,
admitted it had been a "very disappointing night" but stressed the
team could still qualify for Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
"France didn't qualify for the World Cup in 1990 or 1994 and
yet still was chosen to host the World Cup in 1998, so there's no
correlation," he told BBC Radio 4's Today program.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted: "Clearly it would be good for the image of the
game if England not only qualified, but did exceedingly well."
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed claims that the national team was so poor
because there were increasingly fewer English players to select
from domestic teams, particularly in the Premier League.
</P>
<P>
"We haven't been achieving particularly well at the
international level in football for over 25 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I mean we only qualified in four of the last seven World Cups -
we didn't qualify in '74 and '78. There were hardly any foreign
overseas players in our teams at that time."
</P>
<P>
Banks claimed that the presence of top overseas players in the
English game was in fact nurturing better English players.
</P>
<P>
"The English talent coming through is going to be that much
better than previous generations simply because the competition
now is going to be that much harder," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We're not going to have a large number of very ordinary
players -- we're going to have a smaller number of exceptionally
talented players."
</P>
<P>
He added that the creation of the football academies throughout
the Premier League and Division One would enable the national team
to perform at the level that everyone wanted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
