<HEADLINE> Batty Feels No Regret </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Leeds star became the fourth England player to receive a
red card in the last 14 months, following a reckless challenge on
Radoslaw Michalski with seven minutes left in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
But he was in no mood to say sorry, despite seeing the national
team's qualification hopes suffer a potentially fatal blow.
</P>
<P>
"I've got nothing to be ashamed for," Batty said after the
England squad arrived back at Heathrow.
</P>
<P>
"I just play my game and whatever happens, happens.
</P>
<P>
"I've no regrets, whatever I do on the football park. I just go
and enjoy tackles and getting into people.
</P>
<P>
"If I'm late, I'm late -- it doesn't bother me," he said.
</P>
<P>
Batty is confident Sweden will not let England down when they
play Poland next month.
</P>
<P>
The Poles only need a draw in Stockholm to pip England to the
runners-up spot in Group Five after holding Kevin Keegan's men to
a goalless draw on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Batty, who would be suspended for the play-offs if England do
get there, is convinced the Swedes will not take it easy in their
last group game even though they have already qualified for the
European Championships next summer.
</P>
<P>
"I'm looking forward to when Sweden play Poland next month,"
said Batty.
</P>
<P>
"If you're professionals you want to win and I've no doubt that
Sweden will approach it the same way we would."
</P>
<P>
England manager Keegan also believes the Swedes will not allow
Poland an easy ride.
</P>
<P>
"I still believe there is a lifeline there for us, which is
Sweden. They are an excellent side as we found out playing them at
home and I know from the Swedish players in England that they are
very professional.
</P>
<P>
"So we have good things going for us. It's not the way we would
have liked it but that's the way it is," added the boss. 
</P>
