<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Keegan Will Shoulder Blame for Euro Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- England soccer team manager
Kevin Keegan will shoulder the blame if England fail to qualify
for the Euro 2000 play-offs -- but remains as determined as ever
to carry on leading his country.
</P>
<P>
Given the woeful qualifying position in which Keegan found
himself after taking over from Glenn Hoddle, following defeat in
Sweden and a goalless draw at home to Bulgaria, it would perhaps
be easy to point the finger at his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
But then again, even though the draw at Wembley against
Bulgaria was the worst result of the whole campaign, Keegan has
had five competitive games in which to turn the situation around --
and has so far failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
"I have to take responsibility as that's my job. When the FA
offered it to me, I took responsibility for everything that has
happened since I joined that first England squad for the game
against Poland at home," he conceded.
</P>
<P>
"It's not that what happened before doesn't interest me. It may
affect me but there's nothing I could do about it.
</P>
<P>
"I had the chance in the five games to get England through and
I haven't done it yet and now I'm relying on someone else.
</P>
<P>
"But I've always looked at the job and said that I've got three
years until the next World Cup, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Keegan remains confident that Sweden will do England a favour
on October 9 by denying Poland the point they need to clinch a
play-off place at his team's expense.
</P>
<P>
But he struggled to positively answer the direct question of
whether England realistically deserved to make it through what
should admittedly hardly have been the most imposing qualifying
group ever.
</P>
<P>
The stark truth is that England do not deserve a second chance
given the consistent paucity of their displays and although they -
and all English fans - fervently hope that Sweden can do them a
favour, it still hardly bodes well for the finals if they get
there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
