<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Insists International Peacekeeping in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday insisted that the Indonesian government allow
international peacekeepers in East Timor to restore order there.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the White House lawn shortly before
leaving for Auckland, New Zealand, to attend an Asia-Pacific
summit, Clinton said Indonesia would face "dire economic
consequences if it failed to settle the violence in East Timor."
</P>
<P>
"If Indonesia does not end the violence, it must invite -- it
must invite -- the international community to assist in restoring
security," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton predicted "very dire" economic consequences for
Indonesia becauser of the East Timor crisis, saying his
willingness to support future assistance "will depend very
strongly" on the outcome of that crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It would be a pity if the Indonesian recovery were crashed by
this," he said. "But one way or the other it will be crashed by
this if they don't fix it because there'll be overwhelming public
sentiment to stop the international economic cooperation."
</P>
<P>
"Nobody is going to want to continue to invest there if they're
allowing this sort of travesty to go on. I think one way or the
other the economic consequences to them are going to be very
dire," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
