<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Culture Feels at Home in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- When asked why the French people
are interested in the ancient bronzes of China, Professor Ma
Chengyuan, dean of the Shanghai Museum, said that the French are
one of the few in the West who really can appreciate Chinese
culture.
</P>
<P>
He said that the French nation loves civilizations and has a
high level appreciation for arts.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Paris is a city with the highest number of arts
exhibitions in the world proves that the comment of Professor Ma
is true.
</P>
<P>
One week after the China Culture Week opened, two major
cultural events -- the exhibition of the works of 18th century
painter Jean-Baptiste Simeon Chardin and a film on Dutch painter
Rembrandt are inaugurated this week.
</P>
<P>
But what makes Paris special is that it can make an ancient
foreign culture such as that of China feel at home because many
French have shown a close and dear sentiment toward it, and regard
it as their own.
</P>
<P>
During a lecture on Beijing Opera in the China Culture Week, a
retired professor of the prestigious Sorbonne University proposed
to Madame Wang Yuzheng, president of the Beijing Opera Theater,
that Beijing Opera no longer bear the name "opera" because it is
totally different from Western opera.
</P>
<P>
He said that because the French people are already familiar
with such Chinese words as "Qi Gong," China can directly
introduce the word "Jing Xi" into the French language to replace
"Beijing Opera."
</P>
<P>
In terms of sentiment and feeling, the French people are close
with the Chinese because both of them have a long agricultural
tradition and were not good at sea faring.
</P>
<P>
The city of Paris itself has many similarities with Beijing as
both of them have many gates or "porte" on their peripheries,
imperial gardens and palaces.
</P>
<P>
It is not hard to find the striking comparability between the
Arch of Triumph and Qian Men, the Summer Palace and Versaille, the
Forbidden City and Louvre Palace, and Champs-Elysee and Chang An
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
Like the Chinese people, the French people have a brilliant
culture in making furniture and ceramics. But ancient Chinese
furniture and ceramics remain one of the most expensive among
their peers in French auction shops.
</P>
<P>
Victor Hugo, the famous 19th century French writer, had many
Chinese furniture, ceramics and paintings in his house at the
Place des Vosges near the Bastille.
</P>
<P>
As a nation which has been through a long agricultural history,
the French can understand the deep meaning and implications of the
artistic designs and fabrics of ancient China, another great
agricultural civilization.
</P>
<P>
Another thing Chinese and French can share with each other is
humor.
</P>
<P>
One French visitor wrote on the notebook after seeing the
ceramics exhibition of China Culture Week: "I know for the first
time that ceramics can also be humorous. Yes, it is true, how
marvelous!"
</P>
<P>
Many French visitors have become the real appreciators of
Beijing Opera for its subtle movement, actions and gestures, not
to mention the painted masks which deliver all kinds of feelings
ranging from sneer to fury.
</P>
<P>
The difference between French and U.S. movies is that the
former relies more on facial expressions and subtle gestures,
while the latter relies more on actions.
</P>
<P>
The similar point between Chinese and French culture is that
both of them attach great importance to subtlety. 
</P>
</TEXT>
