<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Move Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks were
driven higher by technology companies Thursday despite the U.S.
dollar's decline against the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 43.06 at 11,079.40.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 3.51 at 1,347.66 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 43.28 at 2,852.02.
</P>
<P>
Technology companies were the driving force in the market. IBM
pushed the Dow higher while Yahoo helped the Nasdaq to rise.
</P>
<P>
For much of the trading, the market languished as the dollar
fell from 110.76 yen to 107.67 yen after Japan released a
stronger-than-expected report on its economic growth in the second
quarter. But a later rally lifted the market.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 0.12 at 621.99 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 11.64 at 804.03. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 1.87 at 437.77.
</P>
<P>
Advencing issues were even with decliners on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 1,480 up, 1,478 down and 571 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 766.93 million shares from 779.23
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
