<HEADLINE> Most Italians Says No to Cars in City Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A vast majority of Italians favor
plans to keep most traffic out of the centers of their cities, a
survey published here Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
In what seemed to be a slap in the face for the city council in
the biggest Italian city of Milan that allow cars into historic
city centers, a survey on traffic and pollution carried out by the
Demoskopea polling institute said a full 88 percent of Italians
want no traffic in the heart of their cities.
</P>
<P>
Seven out of 10 Italians would also like to see
pollution-causing two-stroke scooters and mopeds from city
centers, while eight out of 10 would like centers closed off to
cars without a catalytic converter, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
According to Legambiente, the Italian league of environment,
the relaxation of measures to keep cars out of downtown Milan and
Bologna has already led to rising pollution levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
