<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special OAU Summit Calls for Africa's Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIRTE, Libya, September 9 (Xinhua) -- An extraordinary summit
of the Organization of African Unity concluded here on Thursday
with a declaration calling for stronger economic integration, the
establishment of a pan-African parliament and some form of African
union.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said the pan-African parliament should be set
up by next year and the union act be adopted in 2001 at another
summit in Sirte.
</P>
<P>
It stated that the African union should be consistent with
the objectives of OAU charter and the 1991 Abuja Treaty, which
sought to set up an African Economic Community.
</P>
<P>
However, in the declaration, the participants at the summit did
not commit themselves to the establishment of a United States of
Africa as Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi had expected.
</P>
<P>
Still, they commended Gadhafi upon his ``vision for a strong
and united Africa.''
</P>
<P>
The declaration said the 53 OAU members have voiced their
willingness to speed up the implementation of the Abuja Treaty,
which also laid down a series of pan-Africanist measures over
30 years.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of all institutions provided for in the Abuja
Treaty, such as the African Central Bank, the African Monetary
Union, the African Court of Justice and the pan-African
parliament, should be accelerated, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The Abuja agreement is aimed at higher rates of economic growth
and development, improved standards of living, and higher and
sustained rates of investment in the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Gadhafi called for the just-concluded special OAU summit in
July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
